(20, 'General Solid Unit', NULL, 'general-solid-unit', NULL, 'HPLs blister packaging facility is equipped with 8 advanced machines, including the high-speed NOC N 623 from Romaco, Germany, capable of producing 420 blisters per minute. Healthcare Pharmaceuticals Limited maintains a tightly controlled environment with calibrated hygrometers, pressure gauges, and a bubble-type airlock to ensure product integrity. The NOC N 623 supports various packaging modes, such as aluminum-aluminum and aluminum-PVC, with only authorized personnel operating under strict quality protocols.', '<p>Healthcare Pharmaceuticals Limited takes great pride in maintaining the highest standards of quality and efficiency in its packaging operations. A core component ensuring the safe and secure packaging of pharmaceuticals is the blister packaging procedure. To provide insight into this process, we present the blister packaging operation of the NOC N 623 machine, a vital part of Healthcare Pharmaceuticals Limited&rsquo;s extensive packaging capabilities.<br />\r\n<br />\r\nHealthcare Pharmaceuticals Limited is equipped with a total of <strong>8 blister packaging machines</strong>, 7 sourced from Germany, known for their precision and reliability in pharmaceutical manufacturing, and an eighth from Korea, a trusted supplier renowned for innovative engineering. Among these, the <strong>NOC N 623 machine</strong> plays a pivotal role in Healthcare Pharmaceuticals Limited&rsquo;s packaging line.<br />\r\n<br />\r\nBefore entering the blister room, all materials pass through a <strong>material airlock system</strong> designed to maintain optimal conditions. This system ensures that the environment within the blister room remains consistently controlled. The airlock is equipped with a <strong>digital hygrometer</strong> to monitor <strong>temperature</strong> and <strong>humidity</strong> levels, ensuring they meet required specifications. A <strong>pressure gauge</strong> measures the <strong>pressure differential</strong> within the airlock to prevent contamination or deviations from safe operating conditions. Both the hygrometer and pressure gauge are <strong>calibrated</strong> regularly for accuracy.<br />\r\n<br />\r\nThe airlock is designed with <strong>bubble-type seals</strong> and is maintained at <strong>positive pressure</strong> relative to the adjacent corridor and blister room, preventing external contaminants from entering, thereby ensuring the integrity of the packaging process.<br />\r\n<br />\r\nIn addition, a <strong>magnehelic pressure gauge</strong> continuously monitors the <strong>pressure differential</strong> between the blister packaging room and the adjacent secondary packaging room. This monitoring system is essential for maintaining a controlled environment and preventing contamination during the transition between rooms. The magnehelic gauge is also regularly calibrated for precision.<br />\r\n<br />\r\nThe <strong>NOC N 623</strong> is a high-performance blister packaging machine manufactured by <strong>Romaco</strong>, Germany. This advanced machine produces <strong>420 blisters per minute</strong>, ensuring high throughput while maintaining the utmost attention to quality and precision.<br />\r\n<br />\r\nThe NOC N 623 offers versatility in packaging materials. It is designed for various blister packaging modes, including <strong>aluminum-aluminum (aloe aloe)</strong>, <strong>aluminum-PVC (aloe PVC)</strong>, and <strong>aluminum-PVC packaging</strong>, allowing Healthcare Pharmaceuticals Limited to package a wide range of pharmaceutical products, catering to diverse client needs while ensuring optimal product protection.<br />\r\n<br />\r\nTo uphold the highest safety and quality standards, the NOC N 623 machine operates under a strict <strong>authorized personnel protocol</strong>. Only qualified and trained individuals are permitted to operate the machine, ensuring all procedures are meticulously followed and the equipment is used safely.<br />\r\n<br />\r\nFurthermore, <strong>five levels of excess</strong> are in place for quality control and monitoring purposes, designed to detect any deviations from the set parameters and promptly address issues, ensuring all products are packaged according to stringent standards.<br />\r\n<br />\r\nHealthcare Pharmaceuticals Limited&rsquo;s blister packaging process exemplifies a commitment to <strong>quality</strong>, <strong>precision</strong>, and <strong>safety</strong>. With state-of-the-art equipment, stringent environmental controls, and a dedicated team of professionals, Healthcare Pharmaceuticals Limited ensures that every pharmaceutical product is securely and accurately packaged. Whether utilizing the NOC N 623 machine or other packaging lines, Healthcare Pharmaceuticals Limited prioritizes efficiency and strict compliance with regulatory standards, guaranteeing products meet the highest levels of safety and efficacy.</p>', 'blister-packaging-excellence-2025-01-19-678c8ccae22f4.jpg', '2024-12-04 15:49:36', '2025-01-19 23:24:10'),
(21, 'General Powder Unit', NULL, 'general-powder-unit', 'https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=5dOOCwIvaVE', 'Healthcare Pharmaceuticals Limited\'s (HPL) state-of-the-art compression corridor features 7 advanced compression machines, including high-speed models from Germany and Korea, capable of producing 470,400 tablets per hour. The process is tightly controlled, with automated systems ensuring tablet quality, precise weight, and integrity without personal intervention.', '<p style=\"margin-left:0in; margin-right:0in\"><span style=\"font-size:11pt\"><span style=\"font-family:Calibri,sans-serif\">The compression corridor at Healthcare Pharmaceuticals Limited (HPL), where we manage the general waste flow with precision and efficiency. Our material airlock for the compression room is a bubble-type airlock, ensuring a clean and controlled environment. The compression room operates under negative pressure compared to the airlock to maintain the correct pressure differential and prevent contamination.<br />\r\n<br />\r\nHPL&#39;s compression facility houses 7 compression machines, including 6 Fatty compression machines from Germany and 1 Shizong machine from Korea. These high-speed machines run automatically without personnel intervention. The Fatty compression machines are double-channel, featuring 49 die punch stations, with a remarkable capacity to produce 470,400 tablets per hour.<br />\r\n<br />\r\nTo enter the compression room, personnel must undergo a rigorous gowning process. Disposable or reusable garments are stored in designated dress cabinets, and only authorized personnel are permitted to proceed after donning the specified attire in a precise sequence. Protective equipment, such as gloves, goggles, 3M masks, and hand gloves, must be worn during operation to ensure safety.<br />\r\n<br />\r\nOur compression machines are controlled through HMI (Human-Machine Interface), secured by four-level password protection. Each operator has a unique ID and password, ensuring only qualified individuals can operate the machinery. The granules are manually fed into the hopper using an SSS scoop, and the butterfly valve regulates the granule flow.<br />\r\n<br />\r\nInside the machine, the filomatic unit fills the die cavity with granules using three wheels and a fill cam. The dosing unit sets the fill depth via the HMI to control tablet weight precisely. During pre-compression, excess air is expelled from the die cavity, while the main compression roller adjusts tablet hardness and thickness, all monitored and adjusted through the HMI.<br />\r\n<br />\r\nOnce compressed, tablets are ejected via the injection unit, with automatic systems maintaining target tablet weight through force control. Overweight and underweight tablets are automatically rejected. Good tablets pass through tablet shoots, a dedusting unit, and a metal detector before entering the collection drum, all without human intervention.<br />\r\n<br />\r\nA tablet balance is calibrated at the start of each batch and connected to a printer to log weight checks every two hours. Printed records are attached to batch documents. Daily checks include monitoring room conditions, ensuring the metal detector&#39;s performance, and verifying the tablet balance.<br />\r\n<br />\r\nOperators inspect the appearance, size, and shape of tablets during each rotation, recording details such as hardness, thickness, friability, and disintegration time in the Batch Manufacturing Record (BMR). Line clearance is authorized by production and IPQA officers to ensure a seamless process.<br />\r\n<br />\r\nHealthcare Pharmaceuticals Limited&#39;s compression process exemplifies the highest standards of efficiency, automation, and quality control. From precision granule feeding to stringent quality checks, every step ensures that HPL delivers safe, high-quality tablets that meet stringent pharmaceutical standards.</span></span></p>', 'dafault.png', '2024-12-04 16:02:28', '2025-01-19 23:24:28'),
(22, 'Nutrition Facility Solid Unit', NULL, 'nutrition-facility-solid-unit', 'https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=Hx8xALAU-po', 'Healthcare Pharmaceuticals Limited (HPL) operates a state-of-the-art encapsulation facility with six advanced capsule filling machines from Germany, India, and Italy. The encapsulation room maintains strict negative pressure, and capsules are automatically filled, weighed, and checked for quality using the KKE system. Rigorous environmental controls, gowning protocols, and regular monitoring ensure every capsule meets precise pharmaceutical standards for safety, weight, and quality.', '<p style=\"margin-left:0in; margin-right:0in\"><span style=\"font-size:11pt\"><span style=\"font-family:Calibri,sans-serif\">Healthcare Pharmaceuticals Limited (HPL) is proud to present its advanced encapsulation facility, where precision, automation, and quality control are paramount. The encapsulation room operates under strict environmental controls, maintaining negative pressure relative to the corridor to prevent contamination. A magnetic pressure gauge monitors this differential, with a calibration tag confirming accuracy. When the door opens, the pressure reads zero pascal, but once closed, it stabilizes at around 15 pascal, ensuring conditions remain within the required limits for safe and effective production.</span></span><br />\r\n<br />\r\n<span style=\"font-size:11pt\"><span style=\"font-family:Calibri,sans-serif\">The facility is equipped with six state-of-the-art capsule filling and closing machines. Among these, four are Bosch machines from Germany, known for their precision and reliability. Additionally, one PAMAF 19T automatic capsule filling machine from India and one MG2 Planeta 200 machine from Italy contribute to HPL&rsquo;s diverse and robust encapsulation capabilities. To enter the encapsulation room, authorized personnel must follow a gowning process, wearing disposable or reusable garments stored in the designated dress cabinet. Only those listed on the authorized personnel list may operate the machinery, ensuring that all operations are conducted by qualified individuals.</span></span><br />\r\n<br />\r\n<span style=\"font-size:11pt\"><span style=\"font-family:Calibri,sans-serif\">The encapsulation machines are operated through a Human-Machine Interface (HMI) and are equipped with calibration and qualification tags to ensure optimal performance. Capsule shells are automatically transferred to the hopper from the reservoir using compressed air. Similarly, pellets or powder are transferred from their containers to the product hopper and then into the dosing disk. Each machine features twelve stations, each equipped with eighteen segments that hold eighty empty shells. The process begins at stations one and two, where the empty shells are loaded and separated. At station three, cap scanning occurs, ensuring the correct positioning of the capsule cap.</span></span><br />\r\n<br />\r\n<span style=\"font-size:11pt\"><span style=\"font-family:Calibri,sans-serif\">In station five, pellets or powder are filled into the capsule body. For powder, 108 tamping pins are used to ensure accurate filling, while 18 pins are used for pellets. Unseparated capsules are ejected at station seven and removed via vacuum, ensuring only properly filled capsules proceed. Body scanning and closing occur at station nine, while stations ten and eleven transfer the capsules to the polisher unit. Station twelve handles segment cleaning before the cycle restarts, ensuring continuous operation. Stations four, six, and eight remain idle during the filling process but contribute to overall machine function.</span></span><br />\r\n<br />\r\n<span style=\"font-size:11pt\"><span style=\"font-family:Calibri,sans-serif\">Once the capsules are closed, they are transported to the polisher unit before passing through the KKE weight checker. This device ensures that each capsule meets the required weight specifications, automatically rejecting any capsules that fall outside the acceptable range. As 100% of the capsules pass through the weight checker, there is no risk of underweight or overweight capsules continuing to the next stage. The capsules then pass through a metal detector to ensure no contamination has occurred. Capsules meeting all quality standards are collected in containers without any personal intervention, maintaining a seamless and hygienic process.</span></span><br />\r\n<br />\r\n<span style=\"font-size:11pt\"><span style=\"font-family:Calibri,sans-serif\">Even though the KKE system ensures capsule weight accuracy, manual checks are performed every two hours using a table balance connected to a printer. This additional verification step provides an extra layer of quality control. The printed weight records are attached to batch documents, ensuring thorough documentation and compliance with regulatory requirements. Operators also perform regular checks on the encapsulation room conditions, maintain a logbook, and ensure line clearance with production and IPQA officers before each batch.</span></span><br />\r\n<br />\r\n<span style=\"font-size:11pt\"><span style=\"font-family:Calibri,sans-serif\">The encapsulation process at Healthcare Pharmaceuticals Limited is a testament to the company&rsquo;s dedication to quality, precision, and innovation. From automated capsule filling and sealing to rigorous weight control and documentation, every step of the process is meticulously managed to meet the highest pharmaceutical standards.</span></span></p>', 'dafault.png', '2024-12-04 16:16:14', '2025-01-19 23:24:45'),
(23, 'Nutrition Facility Powder Unit', NULL, 'nutrition-facility-powder-unit', 'https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=LMCvNaj0DTE', 'Healthcare Pharmaceuticals Limited (HPL) features a cutting-edge granulation facility equipped with four advanced granulation machinesthree from India and one from Belgium. With strict environmental controls, automated mixing processes, and meticulous granule quality checks, the granulation process ensures consistency and precision in pharmaceutical production.', '<p style=\"margin-left:0in; margin-right:0in\"><span style=\"font-size:11pt\"><span style=\"font-family:Calibri,sans-serif\">At Healthcare Pharmaceuticals Limited (HPL), the granulation process is a cornerstone of our commitment to precision and quality in pharmaceutical manufacturing. The granulation corridor and room maintain strict environmental controls, with a negative pressure differential relative to the corridor to ensure containment and prevent contamination. HPL&rsquo;s granulation facility is equipped with four advanced granulation machines: three from India and one from Belgium, all manufactured by KIA. The granulation room features a KIA Educated Conversion Line, a highly efficient system consisting of three key components: the gear high shear mixer, the gear FBD (Fluid Bed Dryer), and the dry discharge mill.</span></span><br />\r\n<br />\r\n<span style=\"font-size:11pt\"><span style=\"font-family:Calibri,sans-serif\">Before entering the granulation room, authorized personnel must follow a strict gowning protocol. Disposable or reusable garments are stored in the designated dress cabinet, and operators must don these garments in a specific sequence to maintain cleanliness and safety. Only those listed on the authorized personnel list are permitted to operate the granulation machines, ensuring a highly controlled environment. The granulation machines are operated via a Human-Machine Interface (HMI) system, with individual ID and password access for each supervisor and operator. Calibration and qualification tags are prominently displayed on the machines to verify accuracy and compliance.</span></span><br />\r\n<br />\r\n<span style=\"font-size:11pt\"><span style=\"font-family:Calibri,sans-serif\">The granulation process begins with the dispensing of materials into the high shear mixer (PMA 600). Initially, dry mixing is performed to achieve uniformity. Subsequently, a binder solution, binder paste, or pure water is added to the dry mix granules within the high shear mixer. The mixing process occurs at both low and high speeds, with the granulation endpoint determined by monitoring kilowatt readings according to the specifications outlined in the Batch Manufacturing Record (BMR). Once the granulation is complete, the granules are transferred to the Fluid Bed Dryer (FBD) through a closed system to ensure containment and prevent contamination.</span></span><br />\r\n<br />\r\n<span style=\"font-size:11pt\"><span style=\"font-family:Calibri,sans-serif\">In the FBD, the granules undergo precise drying as per BMR guidelines. The endpoint of drying is determined by measuring the Loss on Drying (LOD) as specified in the relevant BMR for the batch. Upon achieving the desired dryness, the granules are transferred to the hopper of the dry discharge mill. To achieve the desired particle size, an appropriate screen is installed in the mill, and the granules are sieved accordingly. The correctly sized granules are then collected in designated containers for further processing.</span></span><br />\r\n<br />\r\n<span style=\"font-size:11pt\"><span style=\"font-family:Calibri,sans-serif\">A floor balance is available in the granulation room to accurately weigh the dispensed materials and the granules during the process. After granulation is complete, reconciliation is performed to ensure that all materials are accounted for, and the final granules are labeled and stored in a Work-In-Progress (WIP) area with appropriate documentation.</span></span><br />\r\n<br />\r\n<span style=\"font-size:11pt\"><span style=\"font-family:Calibri,sans-serif\">Before exiting the granulation room, personnel must remove their outer uniforms and dispose of them in the waste bin provided within the room. Only after completing this step can they exit to the corridor, ensuring that the integrity of the controlled environment is maintained.</span></span><br />\r\n<br />\r\n<span style=\"font-size:11pt\"><span style=\"font-family:Calibri,sans-serif\">HPL&rsquo;s granulation process exemplifies our dedication to quality, precision, and adherence to regulatory standards. From automated mixing and drying to thorough material reconciliation and environmental controls, every step of the process is designed to produce high-quality granules for pharmaceutical applications.</span></span></p>', 'dafault.png', '2024-12-04 16:24:04', '2025-01-19 23:24:57'),
(24, 'Nutrition Facility Liquid Unit', NULL, 'nutrition-facility-liquid-unit', 'https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=MjecK2yraKA', 'Healthcare Pharmaceuticals Limited (HPL) utilizes the Uhlmann BEC 500 blister packaging machine, ensuring high-speed production, precision, and quality. The process includes strict environmental controls, automatic defect detection, and real-time monitoring to guarantee the integrity of every blister pack.', '<p style=\"margin-left:0in; margin-right:0in\"><span style=\"font-size:11pt\"><span style=\"font-family:Calibri,sans-serif\">At Healthcare Pharmaceuticals Limited (HPL), our commitment to high-quality packaging is exemplified in our advanced Uhlmann BEC 500 blister packaging line. This state-of-the-art machine, manufactured by Uhlmann, Germany, is capable of producing up to 500 blisters per minute, delivering high-speed production without compromising on quality. The machine is part of a broader network of eight blister packaging machines in our facility, seven of which are from Germany and one from Korea, known for their precision and reliability.</span></span><br />\r\n<br />\r\n<span style=\"font-size:11pt\"><span style=\"font-family:Calibri,sans-serif\">To maintain an optimal and controlled environment, we utilize a material airlock system located before the blister room. This airlock is a bubble-type design that ensures positive pressure relative to both the corridor and the blister room, minimizing the risk of contamination. Environmental conditions, including temperature, humidity, and pressure differential, are rigorously monitored using calibrated digital hygrometers and pressure gauges. The airlock is further supported by a magnehelic pressure gauge, which ensures the correct pressure differential between the blister room and the secondary packaging room, maintaining safe and sterile conditions.</span></span><br />\r\n<br />\r\n<span style=\"font-size:11pt\"><span style=\"font-family:Calibri,sans-serif\">The Uhlmann BEC 500 offers versatile packaging options, including aluminum-aluminum (alu alu), aluminum-PVC (alu PVC), and aluminum-PVC configurations. The machine is fully qualified and calibrated, operated through a Human-Machine Interface (HMI), and secured with a strict authorized personnel list. Only qualified personnel are authorized to operate this high-precision equipment, ensuring that all processes are carried out according to strict quality protocols.</span></span><br />\r\n<br />\r\n<span style=\"font-size:11pt\"><span style=\"font-family:Calibri,sans-serif\">One key feature of the Uhlmann BEC 500 is the pocket forming station, which is followed by a pinhole detector designed to identify any micro-leakages in the formed pockets. This ensures the integrity of the packaging, especially in alu alu blister packs, where a secure seal is critical. Bulk products are manually loaded into the hopper, and the machine automatically feeds the products into the formed pockets.</span></span><br />\r\n<br />\r\n<span style=\"font-size:11pt\"><span style=\"font-family:Calibri,sans-serif\">To further ensure packaging quality, the Uhlmann BEC 500 is equipped with an advanced camera inspection system that can detect defects such as empty pockets, color variations, broken tablets, and deformed products. A camera challenge test is performed before the start of each batch, and another test is carried out at the end of the packaging cycle to verify that all products meet the required specifications. Any defective blisters are automatically rejected by the machine, reducing the potential for errors.</span></span><br />\r\n<br />\r\n<span style=\"font-size:11pt\"><span style=\"font-family:Calibri,sans-serif\">For example, if an empty pocket is detected during the inspection process, the machine will flag the issue and reject the defective blister. The system is designed to identify and reject not only empty pockets but also blisters with broken tablets, color variation, or pinhole defects. This guarantees that only properly sealed, defect-free blister packs are sent to the next stage of packaging.</span></span><br />\r\n<br />\r\n<span style=\"font-size:11pt\"><span style=\"font-family:Calibri,sans-serif\">Finally, in the sealing and embossing station, the formed and filled pockets are sealed with lead foil, and essential batch information, such as batch number and expiry date, is embossed on the packaging. This ensures complete traceability and compliance with pharmaceutical regulations.</span></span><br />\r\n<br />\r\n<span style=\"font-size:11.0pt\"><span style=\"font-family:&quot;Calibri&quot;,sans-serif\">Through the use of advanced technology, real-time quality monitoring, and automated defect detection, HPL ensures that every blister pack produced in our Uhlmann BEC 500 machine meets the highest standards of quality, safety, and compliance. The precision and efficiency of this process underscore our dedication to delivering pharmaceutical products that our clients can trust.</span></span></p>', 'dafault.png', '2024-12-04 16:35:02', '2025-01-19 23:25:10'),
(25, 'Animal Vaccine Unit', NULL, 'animal-vaccine-unit', 'https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=DL9tWCF0YyY', 'At Healthcare Pharmaceuticals Limited (HPL), our dispensing procedure ensures precision and safety in the handling of raw materials. With strict protocols, including controlled environments and comprehensive checks by authorized personnel, we maintain high standards throughout the dispensing process.', '<p style=\"margin-left:0in; margin-right:0in\"><span style=\"font-size:11pt\"><span style=\"font-family:Calibri,sans-serif\">At Healthcare Pharmaceuticals Limited (HPL), the material dispensing process is a critical part of our manufacturing operations, ensuring the accurate and safe handling of raw materials. The process begins with the submission of a requisition form by the production department to the material management department (MMD), which is then approved with an authorized signature. Once approved, the materials are delivered through the primary hatch to the unweighted material room for initial inspection.<br />\r\n<br />\r\nAfter the cleanliness of the containers is verified, along with the material details, the materials are transferred to the dispensing room, one at a time, based on the specific needs of the production process. The dispensing area is specially designed with a change room, which serves as an entry and exit point for all personnel involved in dispensing activities. Strict entry and exit procedures must be followed by all personnel to maintain the integrity of the process.<br />\r\n<br />\r\nThe dispensing room is maintained under controlled conditions, with negative pressure relative to the surrounding corridor. This ensures that any potential contamination is prevented from entering the dispensing area. A magnehelic pressure gauge is used to monitor the pressure difference between the room and the corridor, and calibration tags are checked to ensure proper functionality. When the door is opened, the gauge reads 0, and when closed, it maintains a pressure differential of approximately 10 pascals, well within the specified limits.<br />\r\n<br />\r\nWithin the dispensing booth, all activities are carefully monitored. The booth is equipped with an HMI (Human-Machine Interface), allowing for precise control and monitoring of the process. The booth also features three gauges that monitor the performance of the pre-filter, intermediate filter, and HEPA filter, with calibration tags on each to ensure proper filtration. Fresh air enters from the top and flows vertically, passing horizontally through the inside grill to prevent air or powder from escaping outside the booth.<br />\r\n<br />\r\nTo ensure precise weighing of materials, a dispensing balance connected to a printer is used. After dispensing the Active Pharmaceutical Ingredient (API), a printout of the transaction is taken and attached to the batch document for traceability and quality control.<br />\r\n<br />\r\nBefore dispensing begins, several safety and operational checks are performed. Personnel are required to wear protective gloves, goggles, masks, and hand covers. The condition of the room is verified, and the balance function is checked. A line clearance is taken from both the production and IPQA (In-Process Quality Assurance) officers. Additionally, the laminar airflow system is run for 15 minutes to ensure the dispensing environment is clean and safe.<br />\r\n<br />\r\nThe dispensing operator receives the materials from the unweighted material room, following verification by the production officer and IPQA officer. These materials are checked for compliance with the material requisition, including the material name, code number, potency, batch or lot number, in-house retail date, and expiration date. Once all the details are verified, the material is transferred into the dispensing booth.<br />\r\n<br />\r\nInside the booth, a clean scoop is selected, and its cleanliness is checked by the production officer. The tare weight of the container, lid, polybag, dispense label, and other related items is then recorded. The required quantity of material is dispensed according to the Batch Manufacturing Record (BMR), and the quantity is double-checked by both the operator and the officers present.<br />\r\n<br />\r\nAfter dispensing, the used scoop is placed in a polybag and stored in a designated container for used items. A printout detailing the dispensed material, date, time, balance model details, product name, batch number, and both net and gross weight is generated. This printout is included in the batch documentation as per standard operating procedures.<br />\r\n<br />\r\nOnce the dispensing operation for a specific API is completed, the broken material container is returned to the unweighted material room, and dispensing continues for the remaining materials in sequence. All dispensed materials are then moved to the WIP (Work in Progress) room, and the dispensing activities are recorded in the logbook to ensure complete traceability and compliance with all regulatory and quality standards.<br />\r\n<br />\r\nAt HPL, we ensure that every step of the dispensing process is conducted with the utmost care, precision, and compliance to provide the highest quality products to our customers.</span></span></p>', 'dafault.png', '2024-12-04 16:43:24', '2025-01-19 23:25:24'),
(26, 'Insulin Unit', NULL, 'insulin-unit', 'https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=dvurWKJlXy4', 'At Healthcare Pharmaceuticals Limited, our General Microbiology Laboratory uses the BiTech 2 Compact Automated Microbial Identification System for rapid and accurate bacterial identification. This system helps identify microorganisms from various sources in less than 24 hours.', '<p style=\"margin-left:0in; margin-right:0in\"><span style=\"font-size:11pt\"><span style=\"font-family:Calibri,sans-serif\">In the General Microbiology Laboratory of Healthcare Pharmaceuticals Limited, after performing media preparation and microbial limit tests, we proceed with microbial identification using the BiTech 2 Compact Automated Microbial Identification System, manufactured by Biomerics USA. This advanced system allows us to efficiently identify microorganisms from various sources, such as the environment and water, with accuracy and speed.</span></span><br />\r\n<br />\r\n<span style=\"font-size:11pt\"><span style=\"font-family:Calibri,sans-serif\">The identification process with this system is both precise and time-saving, usually taking less than 24 hours. To begin, we use different types of identification cards based on the kind of microorganism being tested. For example, the GP card is used for identifying gram-positive bacteria, the GN card for gram-negative bacteria, the ANC card for anaerobic bacteria, the YST card for yeast, and the BCL card for Bacillus species.</span></span><br />\r\n<br />\r\n<span style=\"font-size:11pt\"><span style=\"font-family:Calibri,sans-serif\">The process starts with the Gram staining of the microbial isolate. Based on the Gram stain results, we select the appropriate identification card. The selected colony is then subcultured on a nonselective media, and after incubation, the colony is transferred into a saline solution. The concentration of the solution is measured using the VITAC 2 Densi check machine, which ensures the solution&#39;s concentration matches the required specifications.</span></span><br />\r\n<br />\r\n<span style=\"font-size:11pt\"><span style=\"font-family:Calibri,sans-serif\">Once the concentration is adjusted, the sample information, including the identification reference number, cassette number, and McFarland concentration, is entered into the system&rsquo;s software. The selected identification card is then inserted into a tube, and the tube is placed into the machine along with the cassette. The system automatically loads the card, performs the identification process, and generates a detailed report with the results.</span></span><br />\r\n<br />\r\n<span style=\"font-size:11pt\"><span style=\"font-family:Calibri,sans-serif\">This bacterial identification system enhances the efficiency of our microbiological testing, providing quick, accurate results that are essential for ensuring the quality and safety of our pharmaceutical products.</span></span></p>', 'dafault.png', '2024-12-04 16:56:12', '2025-01-19 23:25:57'),
(27, 'Human Vaccine Unit', NULL, 'human-vaccine-unit', 'https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=YltDMhinWB0', 'At Healthcare Pharmaceuticals Limited, we follow a precise procedure for microbiological culture media preparation. Using dehydrated media, the process includes careful weighing, dissolution, sterilization, and quality checks before use in testing.', '<p style=\"margin-left:0in; margin-right:0in\"><span style=\"font-size:11pt\"><span style=\"font-family:Calibri,sans-serif\">In the microbiological culture media preparation area of Healthcare Pharmaceuticals Limited, we use dehydrated microbiological media for preparing our culture media. Upon receipt, each media bottle undergoes a thorough inspection and is tagged with a quarantine label. The first step is to conduct growth promotion testing to ensure the quality of the media. Once the testing is complete, the bottles are relabeled with an approved level tag and are ready for use.</span></span><br />\r\n<br />\r\n<span style=\"font-size:11pt\"><span style=\"font-family:Calibri,sans-serif\">For media preparation, we gather specific glassware and accessories such as a spookab bottle, measuring cylinder, and spoon. Purified water is also required to dissolve the dehydrated media. The first task is to calculate the amount of media needed for preparation based on the specific requirements.</span></span><br />\r\n<br />\r\n<span style=\"font-size:11pt\"><span style=\"font-family:Calibri,sans-serif\">Once the amount is determined, the dehydrated media is weighed on a calibrated balance. The media is then added to the bottle, which contains half the required volume of purified water. The bottle is carefully labeled with the name of the media, preparation reference number, preparation date, and the signature of the personnel who prepared the media.</span></span><br />\r\n<br />\r\n<span style=\"font-size:11pt\"><span style=\"font-family:Calibri,sans-serif\">After the media is added, it is agitated briskly to mix thoroughly. The remaining purified water is then added to the bottle, and the mixture is placed in a water bath to ensure complete dissolution. A weight print of the media is recorded in the media preparation logbook, and the exact weight is also logged in the respective analytical balance logbook.</span></span><br />\r\n<br />\r\n<span style=\"font-size:11pt\"><span style=\"font-family:Calibri,sans-serif\">Following the preparation process, the media undergoes sterilization in a double-door autoclave, which is set to validated sterilization cycles. Once sterilized, the media is ready for use in microbiological testing and is dispensed according to the requirements of the respective tests.</span></span><br />\r\n<br />\r\n<span style=\"font-size:11pt\"><span style=\"font-family:Calibri,sans-serif\">This detailed procedure ensures that all microbiological culture media is prepared to the highest standards of quality and precision, guaranteeing reliable results in our laboratory tests.</span></span></p>', 'dafault.png', '2024-12-04 17:04:58', '2025-01-19 23:26:11'),
(28, 'Biotec Unit', NULL, 'biotec-unit', 'https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=0-2FoEuua7Q', 'At Healthcare Pharmaceuticals Limited, microbial enumeration or limit testing is performed on oral solid dosages to ensure product safety. The process involves sample preparation, media preparation, and incubation to detect microbial contamination.', '<p style=\"margin-left:0in; margin-right:0in\"><span style=\"font-size:11pt\"><span style=\"font-family:Calibri,sans-serif\">Healthcare Pharmaceuticals Limited will demonstrate the procedure for the microbial enumeration test (limit test) for oral solid dosages. Upon receiving the sample, it is carefully logged and transferred to the limit test room via a dynamic pass box, where it is stored in a secure sample custody area until testing begins.</span></span><br />\r\n<br />\r\n<span style=\"font-size:11pt\"><span style=\"font-family:Calibri,sans-serif\">The microbial enumeration test is conducted under a biological safety cabinet. Before starting, all necessary accessories such as sterile screwcap bottles, sterile petri plates, sterile tips, and pipettes are gathered. The test process begins by documenting the relevant details in a logbook.</span></span><br />\r\n<br />\r\n<span style=\"font-size:11pt\"><span style=\"font-family:Calibri,sans-serif\">For testing, the sample is first checked, and details including the media name, product name, batch number, and testing day are recorded on the bottle used for weighing the sample. For this test, two types of media are used: tryptic soy agar (TSA) for total yeast and mold counts, and a diluent for preparation.</span></span><br />\r\n<br />\r\n<span style=\"font-size:11pt\"><span style=\"font-family:Calibri,sans-serif\">To prepare a 10-gram sample from an oral solid dosage (typically tablets), Healthcare Pharmaceuticals Limited weighs one tablet and calculates the total number of tablets needed to achieve a 10-gram sample. A balance printout is recorded and attached to the analytical worksheet specific to the product. The diluent is then added to the bottle containing the tablets, making up to 100 ml and achieving a 10-fold dilution.</span></span><br />\r\n<br />\r\n<span style=\"font-size:11pt\"><span style=\"font-family:Calibri,sans-serif\">Next, four petri plates are labeled with the media name, day, product name, and batch number. Two plates are kept as negative controls, one for each media type. 1 ml of the prepared sample is pipetted onto each of the four petri plates, and 1 ml of diluent is added to the negative control plates. The appropriate media are poured into the plates and mixed by rotating the plates clockwise and anticlockwise.</span></span><br />\r\n<br />\r\n<span style=\"font-size:11pt\"><span style=\"font-family:Calibri,sans-serif\">Once the agar solidifies, the petri plates are inverted and incubated. The TSA plates are incubated at 30-35&deg;C, and the SDA plates are incubated at 20-25&deg;C for 5 days.</span></span><br />\r\n<br />\r\n<span style=\"font-size:11pt\"><span style=\"font-family:Calibri,sans-serif\">This procedure ensures that the oral solid dosage is free from microbial contamination and complies with regulatory standards for microbial limits. This concludes the microbial enumeration test or limit test process at Healthcare Pharmaceuticals Limited.</span></span></p>', 'dafault.png', '2024-12-04 17:14:05', '2025-01-19 23:26:32');
