(126, '27', 'What is Andep used for?', 'Andep is indicated for treating Major Depressive Disorder (MDD), Obsessive-Compulsive Disorder (OCD), Panic Disorder (PD), Post-Traumatic Stress Disorder (PTSD), Social Anxiety Disorder (SAD), and Premenstrual Dysphoric Disorder (PMDD).', 'what-is-andep-used-for', NULL, '2024-10-17 10:46:37', '2024-10-17 10:46:37'),
(127, '27', 'What is the starting dose for Major Depressive Disorder (MDD) in adults?', 'The starting dose is 50 mg, with a therapeutic range of 50-200 mg.', 'what-is-the-starting-dose-for-major-depressive-disorder-mdd-in-adults', NULL, '2024-10-17 10:47:10', '2024-10-17 10:47:10'),
(128, '27', 'What is the starting dose for Panic Disorder, PTSD, and SAD in adults?', 'The starting dose is 25 mg, with a therapeutic range of 50-200 mg.', 'what-is-the-starting-dose-for-panic-disorder-ptsd-and-sad-in-adults', NULL, '2024-10-17 10:47:41', '2024-10-17 10:47:41'),
(129, '27', 'What is the pediatric dose for Obsessive-Compulsive Disorder (ages 6-12)?', 'The starting dose is 25 mg, with a therapeutic range of 50-200 mg.', 'what-is-the-pediatric-dose-for-obsessive-compulsive-disorder-ages-6-12', NULL, '2024-10-17 10:48:12', '2024-10-17 10:48:12'),
(130, '27', 'Can Andep be used during pregnancy or breastfeeding?', 'The safety during pregnancy has not been established, and Sertraline is excreted in breast milk. Discontinuation of breastfeeding should be considered if treatment is necessary.', 'can-andep-be-used-during-pregnancy-or-breastfeeding', NULL, '2024-10-17 10:48:47', '2024-10-17 10:48:47'),
(131, '27', 'What are the common side effects of Andep?', 'Side effects include upset stomach, diarrhea, constipation, dry mouth, dizziness, drowsiness, headache, and weight changes.', 'what-are-the-common-side-effects-of-andep', NULL, '2024-10-17 10:49:21', '2024-10-17 10:49:21'),
(132, '27', 'What precautions should be taken while using Andep?', 'Precautions are needed for liver/kidney problems, heart issues, seizures, and allergies. Caution is also advised for activities requiring alertness and in elderly patients.', 'what-precautions-should-be-taken-while-using-andep', NULL, '2024-10-17 10:49:44', '2024-10-17 10:49:44'),
(133, '27', 'How should Andep be stored?', 'Store below 30C and keep out of reach of children', 'how-should-andep-be-stored', NULL, '2024-10-17 10:50:07', '2024-10-17 10:50:07'),
(134, '30', 'What are the indications for Cisplatin?', ': Cisplatin is indicated as palliative therapy and in established combination therapy for the following conditions:\r\n\r\nMetastatic Testicular Tumors: In patients who have received appropriate surgical and/or radiotherapeutic and/or chemotherapeutic procedures.\r\nMetastatic Ovarian Tumors: As secondary therapy in patients who are refractory to standard chemotherapy.\r\nAdvanced Bladder Cancer: As a single agent for patients with transitional cell bladder cancer.\r\nNon-Small Cell Lung Carcinoma: In combination with other chemotherapeutic agents for patients not candidates for curative surgery and/or radiation therapy.', 'what-are-the-indications-for-cisplatin', NULL, '2024-10-29 15:32:02', '2024-10-29 15:32:02'),
(135, '30', 'How does Cisplatin work?', 'Cisplatin is a platinum compound that produces intra- and interstrand cross-links in DNA, modifying its structure and inhibiting DNA synthesis. It also inhibits protein and RNA synthesis but is not phase-specific in the cell cycle.', 'how-does-cisplatin-work', NULL, '2024-10-29 15:32:38', '2024-10-29 15:32:38'),
(136, '30', 'What is the usual dosage for Cisplatin in metastatic testicular tumors?', 'The usual dose is 20 mg/m IV daily for 5 days per cycle in combination with other approved chemotherapeutic agents.', 'what-is-the-usual-dosage-for-cisplatin-in-metastatic-testicular-tumors', NULL, '2024-10-29 15:33:09', '2024-10-29 15:33:09'),
(137, '30', 'What is the recommended dosage for advanced bladder cancer?', 'Cisplatin should be administered at a dose of 50 to 70 mg/m IV per cycle every 3 to 4 weeks, depending on prior exposure to radiation and chemotherapy.', 'what-is-the-recommended-dosage-for-advanced-bladder-cancer', NULL, '2024-10-29 15:33:47', '2024-10-29 15:33:47'),
(138, '30', 'What is the dosage for non-small cell lung carcinoma?', 'Cisplatin is administered at 75 mg/m in combination with Paclitaxel (135 mg/m) every three weeks.', 'what-is-the-dosage-for-non-small-cell-lung-carcinoma', NULL, '2024-10-29 15:34:08', '2024-10-29 15:34:08'),
(139, '30', 'What are the important drug interactions with Cisplatin?', 'Significant interactions include:\r\n\r\nNephrotoxic Drugs: Avoid concurrent use with aminoglycoside antibiotics and other nephrotoxic agents.\r\nOtotoxic Drugs: Concurrent use may increase the risk of ototoxicity.\r\nRenally Excreted Drugs: May enhance toxicity of drugs like bleomycin and methotrexate.\r\nAnticonvulsants: Serum levels of phenytoin may decrease, requiring monitoring and dosage adjustments.\r\nAntigout Agents: Dosage adjustments may be necessary to control hyperuricemia.\r\nContraindications', 'what-are-the-important-drug-interactions-with-cisplatin', NULL, '2024-10-29 15:34:34', '2024-10-29 15:34:34'),
(140, '30', 'When is Cisplatin contraindicated?', 'Cisplatin is contraindicated in patients with:\r\n\r\nPre-existing renal impairment.\r\nHistory of hypersensitivity to Cisplatin or platinum compounds.\r\nMyelosuppression.\r\nHearing impairment.', 'when-is-cisplatin-contraindicated', NULL, '2024-10-29 15:35:13', '2024-10-29 15:35:13'),
(141, '30', 'What are the common side effects of Cisplatin?', 'Common side effects include:\r\n\r\nSevere nausea and vomiting (usually starts 1-4 hours post-treatment).\r\nElectrolyte disturbances (e.g., hypomagnesemia, hypocalcemia, hypokalemia).\r\nSymptoms of electrolyte imbalances may include muscle irritability, cramps, or tetany.', 'what-are-the-common-side-effects-of-cisplatin', NULL, '2024-10-29 15:35:39', '2024-10-29 15:35:39'),
(142, '30', 'What is the pregnancy category of Cisplatin?', 'Cisplatin is classified as Pregnancy Category D, indicating risk to the fetus. It may also be found in human milk, but it is unknown if it is excreted in human milk.', 'what-is-the-pregnancy-category-of-cisplatin', NULL, '2024-10-29 15:36:12', '2024-10-29 15:36:12'),
(143, '30', 'What precautions should be taken when administering Cisplatin?', 'Precautions include:\r\n\r\nRenal Function: Monitor renal function and electrolytes before and during treatment. Administer adequate hydration.\r\nBone Marrow Function: Frequent blood count monitoring is necessary.\r\nHearing Function: Audiometry should be performed before and during treatment.\r\nCNS Functions: Neurological examinations should be conducted due to the risk of neurotoxicity.\r\nNausea and Vomiting: Prepare for significant nausea and vomiting; administer only under the supervision of experienced physicians.\r\nCarcinogenicity: Be aware of the potential risk of secondary malignancies with long-term use.', 'what-precautions-should-be-taken-when-administering-cisplatin', NULL, '2024-10-29 15:36:43', '2024-10-29 15:36:43'),
(144, '30', 'What are the effects of Cisplatin overdose?', 'Overdose may result in kidney failure, liver failure, deafness, ocular toxicity, significant myelosuppression, severe nausea and vomiting, and potentially death. There are no proven antidotes, and management includes general supportive care.', 'what-are-the-effects-of-cisplatin-overdose', NULL, '2024-10-29 15:37:10', '2024-10-29 15:37:10'),
(145, '30', 'What is the therapeutic class of Cisplatin?', 'Cisplatin belongs to the class of cytotoxic chemotherapy agents.', 'what-is-the-therapeutic-class-of-cisplatin', NULL, '2024-10-29 15:37:36', '2024-10-29 15:37:36'),
(146, '30', 'How should Cisplatin be stored?', 'Store the vial in the original carton at 25C. Do not refrigerate. Protect from light and keep out of the reach of children.', 'how-should-cisplatin-be-stored', NULL, '2024-10-29 15:38:09', '2024-10-29 15:38:09'),
(147, '32', 'What are the indications for Letrozole?', ': Letrozole is indicated for:\r\nAdjuvant treatment of postmenopausal women with hormone receptor-positive early breast cancer.\r\nExtended adjuvant therapy in postmenopausal women with early breast cancer who have received 5 years of tamoxifen therapy.\r\nFirst-line treatment in postmenopausal women with hormone-dependent advanced breast cancer.\r\nTreatment of advanced breast cancer in women with postmenopausal status previously treated with antioestrogens.\r\nPre-operative therapy in postmenopausal women with localized hormone receptor-positive breast cancer to allow for breast-conserving surgery.', 'what-are-the-indications-for-letrozole', NULL, '2024-10-29 22:45:58', '2024-10-29 22:45:58'),
(148, '32', 'How does Letrozole work (Mechanism of Action)?', 'Letrozole is a nonsteroidal aromatase inhibitor that binds to the haem of the enzyme cytochrome P450. This competitive inhibition reduces estrogen biosynthesis, depriving estrogen-dependent breast cancer cells of their growth stimulus.', 'how-does-letrozole-work-mechanism-of-action', NULL, '2024-10-29 22:46:24', '2024-10-29 22:46:24'),
(149, '32', 'What are the pharmacokinetic properties of Letrozole?', 'Letrozole is absorbed fully from the gastrointestinal tract with an absolute bioavailability of 99.9%. It is moderately bound to plasma proteins (60%) and is metabolized primarily in the liver, with a terminal elimination half-life of around 2 days. Steady-state levels are reached within 2-6 weeks at a daily dose of 2.5 mg.', 'what-are-the-pharmacokinetic-properties-of-letrozole', NULL, '2024-10-29 22:46:51', '2024-10-29 22:46:51'),
(150, '32', 'What is the recommended dosage for Letrozole in adults and elderly patients?', 'The recommended dose is 2.5 mg once daily. For adjuvant and extended adjuvant therapy, treatment should continue for 5 years or until tumor relapse. In metastatic cases, treatment should continue until tumor progression. No dose adjustment is needed for elderly patients.', 'what-is-the-recommended-dosage-for-letrozole-in-adults-and-elderly-patients', NULL, '2024-10-29 22:47:17', '2024-10-29 22:47:17'),
(151, '32', 'Are there specific dosage adjustments required for patients with hepatic or renal impairment?', 'Generally, no adjustment is required for patients with hepatic or renal impairment (creatinine clearance 10 mL/min), but close supervision is advised for those with severe hepatic impairment.', 'are-there-specific-dosage-adjustments-required-for-patients-with-hepatic-or-renal-impairment', NULL, '2024-10-29 22:48:17', '2024-10-29 22:48:17'),
(152, '32', 'Are there any known drug interactions with Letrozole?', 'Co-administration with cimetidine and warfarin has shown no clinically significant interactions. Caution may be warranted with other medications processed by cytochrome P450 enzymes.', 'are-there-any-known-drug-interactions-with-letrozole', NULL, '2024-10-29 22:48:35', '2024-10-29 22:48:35'),
(153, '32', 'What are the common side effects of Letrozole?', 'Common side effects include hot flashes, increased cholesterol, fatigue, sweating, bone and joint pain, rash, headache, dizziness, gastrointestinal issues, appetite changes, osteoporosis, edema, depression, weight changes, hypertension, and dry skin.', 'what-are-the-common-side-effects-of-letrozole', NULL, '2024-10-29 22:49:02', '2024-10-29 22:49:02'),
(154, '32', 'Is Letrozole safe for use during pregnancy and lactation?', 'Letrozole is contraindicated during pregnancy and lactation due to potential teratogenicity and fetal toxicity', 'is-letrozole-safe-for-use-during-pregnancy-and-lactation', NULL, '2024-10-29 22:49:34', '2024-10-29 22:49:34'),
(155, '32', 'What precautions should be taken with Letrozole?', 'Caution is advised for patients with moderate hepatic dysfunction. Fatigue and dizziness may occur, so patients should avoid activities requiring full alertness, such as driving.', 'what-precautions-should-be-taken-with-letrozole', NULL, '2024-10-29 22:50:02', '2024-10-29 22:50:02'),
(156, '32', 'What should be done in case of an overdose of Letrozole?', 'Supportive care and monitoring are recommended. Dialysis may be beneficial as Letrozole is weakly protein-bound.', 'what-should-be-done-in-case-of-an-overdose-of-letrozole', NULL, '2024-10-29 22:50:25', '2024-10-29 22:50:25'),
(157, '32', 'How should Letrozole be stored?', 'Letrozole should be stored below 30C, away from light and moisture, and out of reach of children.', 'how-should-letrozole-be-stored', NULL, '2024-10-29 22:50:50', '2024-10-29 22:50:50'),
(158, '35', 'What is Daunobin indicated for?', 'Daunobin, combined with other anticancer drugs, is indicated for remission induction in adult acute nonlymphocytic leukemia and both adult and pediatric acute lymphocytic leukemia.', 'what-is-daunobin-indicated-for', NULL, '2024-10-30 13:16:25', '2024-10-30 13:16:25'),
(159, '35', 'How does Daunorubicin work?', 'Daunorubicin works by intercalating DNA, inhibiting topoisomerase II, and causing DNA strand breaks, which collectively lead to cytotoxic and antitumor effects.', 'how-does-daunorubicin-work', NULL, '2024-10-30 13:16:45', '2024-10-30 13:16:45'),
(160, '35', 'What are the main side effects?', 'Key side effects include myelosuppression, cardiotoxicity, alopecia, mild nausea, and tissue necrosis if extravasation occurs during IV administration.', 'what-are-the-main-side-effects', NULL, '2024-10-30 13:17:06', '2024-10-30 13:17:06'),
(161, '35', 'Are there any contraindications?', 'Yes, Daunobin is contraindicated in patients with hypersensitivity to Daunorubicin or similar compounds.', 'are-there-any-contraindications', NULL, '2024-10-30 13:17:32', '2024-10-30 13:17:32'),
(162, '35', 'What precautions should be taken with Daunobin?', 'Monitor blood counts, cardiac, renal, and hepatic function, and use caution in patients with liver impairment or infection. Daunobin should be administered by experienced physicians in equipped facilities.', 'what-precautions-should-be-taken-with-daunobin', NULL, '2024-10-30 13:17:52', '2024-10-30 13:17:52'),
(163, '35', 'How is Daunobin stored and handled?', 'Store in a refrigerator (2-8C) and protect from light. Avoid skin contact; wash thoroughly if contact occurs.', 'how-is-daunobin-stored-and-handled', NULL, '2024-10-30 13:18:12', '2024-10-30 13:18:12'),
(164, '33', 'What is the composition of Potacit?', 'Each 5 ml of oral solution contains Potassium Citrate BP 1.5 g and Citric Acid Monohydrate BP 273.425 mg, equivalent to Citric Acid 250 mg.', 'what-is-the-composition-of-potacit', NULL, '2024-11-04 16:03:25', '2024-11-04 16:03:25'),
(165, '33', 'What are the indications for using Potacit?', 'It is used for the symptomatic relief of dysuria associated with mild urinary tract infections, particularly cystitis.', 'what-are-the-indications-for-using-potacit', NULL, '2024-11-04 16:03:45', '2024-11-04 16:03:45'),
(166, '33', 'What is the recommended dosage and administration of Potacit?', 'Adults, including the elderly, and children over 6 years: 10 ml of Potacit solution three times daily after meals.\r\nChildren under 6 years: 5 ml of Potacit solution three times daily after meals.\r\nThe solution should be diluted in a glass of water (250 ml) and may be followed by additional water if desired.', 'what-is-the-recommended-dosage-and-administration-of-potacit', NULL, '2024-11-04 16:04:08', '2024-11-04 16:04:08'),
(167, '33', 'What are the potential side effects of Potacit?', 'Mild nausea and occasional vomiting may occur due to gastric irritation.', 'what-are-the-potential-side-effects-of-potacit', NULL, '2024-11-04 16:04:35', '2024-11-04 16:04:35'),
(168, '33', 'Are there any contraindications for Potacit?', 'Yes, it is contraindicated in cases of hyperkalemia, renal dysfunction, ventricular arrhythmias, and known hypersensitivity to Potassium Citrate or any other ingredient.', 'are-there-any-contraindications-for-potacit', NULL, '2024-11-04 16:04:57', '2024-11-04 16:04:57'),
(169, '33', 'What precautions should be taken when using Potacit?', 'This solution provides symptomatic relief only and is not an antibacterial. Effective antibacterial therapy should be co-prescribed. It should be used with caution in patients with renal or cardiac dysfunction.', 'what-precautions-should-be-taken-when-using-potacit', NULL, '2024-11-04 16:05:17', '2024-11-04 16:05:17'),
(170, '33', 'What drug interactions should be considered when taking Potacit?', 'Concurrent use of potassium-containing or potassium-sparing medications may lead to hyperkalemia. It may also interact with cardiac glycosides.', 'what-drug-interactions-should-be-considered-when-taking-potacit', NULL, '2024-11-04 16:05:43', '2024-11-04 16:05:43'),
(171, '33', 'Is Potacit safe to use during pregnancy and lactation?', 'No adverse effects are anticipated at the recommended dose when used solely for initial symptomatic relief. Treatment with this solution is adjunctive to antibacterial therapy for urinary tract infections.', 'is-potacit-safe-to-use-during-pregnancy-and-lactation', NULL, '2024-11-04 16:06:05', '2024-11-04 16:06:05'),
(172, '33', 'What are the signs of overdose with Potacit?', 'Overdose may result in nausea, vomiting, abdominal pain, and symptoms associated with hyperkalemia and metabolic acidosis.', 'what-are-the-signs-of-overdose-with-potacit', NULL, '2024-11-04 16:06:25', '2024-11-04 16:06:25'),
(173, '33', 'How should Potacit be stored?', 'Store at a temperature not exceeding 30 C in a dry place, and protect from light.', 'how-should-potacit-be-stored', NULL, '2024-11-04 16:06:46', '2024-11-04 16:06:46'),
(174, '36', 'What drug interactions should I be aware of when using Cleocin (Clindamycin)?', 'Cleocin enhances the effect of neuromuscular blocking agents and should be used cautiously with patients receiving these drugs. There is antagonism between Cleocin and erythromycin, so these two drugs should not be used together.', 'what-drug-interactions-should-i-be-aware-of-when-using-cleocin-clindamycin', NULL, '2024-11-04 16:21:47', '2024-11-04 16:21:47'),
(175, '36', 'Who should not take Clindamycin (Cleocin)?', 'Clindamycin is contraindicated for patients who are sensitive to clindamycin or any other ingredients in this medication.', 'who-should-not-take-clindamycin-cleocin', NULL, '2024-11-04 16:22:06', '2024-11-04 16:22:06'),
(176, '36', 'What are the possible side effects of Cleocin?', 'The common side effects include abdominal pain, esophagitis, esophageal ulcer, nausea, vomiting, diarrhea, itching (pruritus), skin rashes, and hives (urticaria).', 'what-are-the-possible-side-effects-of-cleocin', NULL, '2024-11-04 16:22:37', '2024-11-04 16:22:37'),
(177, '36', 'Can pregnant or breastfeeding women use Cleocin?', 'Cleocin falls under Pregnancy Category B. It crosses the placenta, and its concentration in amniotic fluid is approximately 30% of the maternal concentration. It should only be used during pregnancy if absolutely necessary. Clindamycin may also appear in breast milk, so it is not recommended for nursing mothers unless clearly needed.', 'can-pregnant-or-breastfeeding-women-use-cleocin', NULL, '2024-11-04 16:23:01', '2024-11-04 16:23:01'),
(178, '36', 'What precautions should be taken when using Cleocin?', 'Cleocin should be used with caution in patients with a history of gastrointestinal disease, particularly colitis.', 'what-precautions-should-be-taken-when-using-cleocin', NULL, '2024-11-04 16:23:13', '2024-11-04 16:23:13'),
(179, '36', 'Is Clindamycin safe for newborns and elderly patients?', 'For newborns and infants (up to 16 years old), organ functions should be carefully monitored while taking Cleocin. For elderly patients, no dosage adjustment is typically necessary.', 'is-clindamycin-safe-for-newborns-and-elderly-patients', NULL, '2024-11-04 16:23:30', '2024-11-04 16:23:30'),
(180, '36', 'What should I do in case of an overdose of Cleocin?', 'Overdosage of Cleocin is rare, but similar adverse reactions to those seen with regular doses may occur. Unexpected reactions could happen, and in such cases, simple gastric lavage may be performed. Haemodialysis and peritoneal dialysis are not effective in removing Cleocin from the body. No specific antidote is known.', 'what-should-i-do-in-case-of-an-overdose-of-cleocin', NULL, '2024-11-04 16:23:47', '2024-11-04 16:23:47'),
(181, '36', 'What storage conditions are required for Cleocin?', 'Store Cleocin below 30C, away from light and moisture. Keep the medication out of the reach of children.', 'what-storage-conditions-are-required-for-cleocin', NULL, '2024-11-04 16:24:12', '2024-11-04 16:24:12'),
(182, '40', 'What is the composition of Laxante Tablet?', 'Each Laxante Tablet contains Sodium Picosulfate BP 10 mg.', 'what-is-the-composition-of-laxante-tablet', NULL, '2024-11-04 16:53:20', '2024-11-04 16:53:20'),
(183, '40', 'What is the pharmacology of Sodium Picosulfate?', 'Sodium Picosulfate is a triarylmethane derivative stimulant laxative. After oral administration, it is activated by colonic bacteria and acts locally in the colon, stimulating nerve endings in the intestinal wall, which results in colonic peristalsis, promotes the accumulation of water and electrolytes, and leads to defecation, reduced transit time, and softened stool. It also stimulates the rectum, increasing motility and the feeling of rectal fullness, helping to restore the \"call to stool.\"', 'what-is-the-pharmacology-of-sodium-picosulfate', NULL, '2024-11-04 16:53:39', '2024-11-04 16:53:39'),
(184, '40', 'What are the indications for Sodium Picosulfate?', 'Sodium Picosulfate is indicated for:\r\nConstipation of any etiology\r\nRelief from prolonged and recurrent constipation\r\nBowel clearance before surgery, childbirth, or radiological investigations.', 'what-are-the-indications-for-sodium-picosulfate', NULL, '2024-11-04 16:54:08', '2024-11-04 16:54:08'),
(185, '40', 'Is Sodium Picosulfate safe to use during pregnancy and lactation?', 'There are no reports of undesirable or damaging effects during pregnancy or to the fetus attributable to this product. However, use should be avoided during the first trimester. Clinical data indicate that neither the active form of sodium Picosulfate nor its glucuronides are excreted into the milk of healthy lactating females.', 'is-sodium-picosulfate-safe-to-use-during-pregnancy-and-lactation', NULL, '2024-11-04 16:54:37', '2024-11-04 16:54:37'),
(186, '40', 'What are the potential drug interactions with Sodium Picosulfate?', 'Concomitant use of diuretics or adrenocorticosteroids may increase the risk of electrolyte imbalance if excessive doses are taken. Concurrent administration of antibiotics may reduce the laxative action of this product.', 'what-are-the-potential-drug-interactions-with-sodium-picosulfate', NULL, '2024-11-04 16:54:57', '2024-11-04 16:54:57'),
(187, '40', 'What are the effects of an overdose of Laxante?', 'Chronic overdosage may lead to chronic diarrhea, abdominal pain, hypokalemia, secondary hyperaldosteronism, and renal calculi. It may also result in renal tubular damage, metabolic alkalosis, and muscle weakness secondary to hypokalemia.', 'what-are-the-effects-of-an-overdose-of-laxante', NULL, '2024-11-04 16:55:15', '2024-11-04 16:55:15'),
(188, '40', 'What precautions and warnings should be considered?', 'Prolonged excessive use may lead to fluid and electrolyte imbalance and hypokalemia. It may be harmful for individuals suffering from alcoholism and should be used cautiously in pregnant or breastfeeding women, children, and high-risk groups such as patients with liver disease or epilepsy.', 'what-precautions-and-warnings-should-be-considered', NULL, '2024-11-04 16:55:38', '2024-11-04 16:55:38'),
(189, '40', 'What are the possible side effects of Laxante?', 'Possible side effects include hypersensitivity, dizziness, syncope, vasovagal response, gastrointestinal disorders, diarrhea, abdominal pain and cramps, nausea, and vomiting.', 'what-are-the-possible-side-effects-of-laxante', NULL, '2024-11-04 16:55:58', '2024-11-04 16:55:58'),
(190, '40', 'How should Laxante be stored?', 'Store Laxante at a temperature not exceeding 30 C in a dry place, protected from light and moisture.', 'how-should-laxante-be-stored', NULL, '2024-11-04 16:56:19', '2024-11-04 16:56:19'),
(191, '41', 'What are the indications for Levothyroxine?', 'Levothyroxine is indicated for replacement therapy in hypothyroidism of any etiology, but should not be used in transient hypothyroidism during the recovery phase of subacute thyroiditis. It is also used to suppress Thyroid Stimulating Hormone (TSH) levels in the presence of goiters, nodules, and after radiological or surgical treatment of thyroid cancer. Additionally, it suppresses the goitrogenic effects of medications like lithium and serves as a diagnostic aid in suppression tests.', 'what-are-the-indications-for-levothyroxine', NULL, '2024-11-04 17:08:06', '2024-11-04 17:08:06'),
(192, '41', 'What is the pharmacology of Levothyroxine?', 'Levothyroxine (T4) is a synthetic thyroid hormone identical to the natural hormone produced by the thyroid gland. About 30% of T4 is converted to the more active Triiodothyronine (T3) in peripheral tissues. T4 is primarily carried by Thyroxine Binding Globulin (TBG), which protects it from metabolism and extends its circulation half-life (6-7 days). In hyperthyroidism, this half-life shortens to 3-4 days, while in hypothyroidism, it may increase to 9-10 days. The liver is responsible for degrading thyroid hormones, which can be reabsorbed through enterohepatic circulation. A steady blood level of T3 is achieved with a single daily dose of levothyroxine, minimizing variations in therapeutic effect once the correct dosage is established.', 'what-is-the-pharmacology-of-levothyroxine', NULL, '2024-11-04 17:08:25', '2024-11-04 17:08:25'),
(193, '41', 'What is the recommended dosage for Levothyroxine?', 'Adults: The initial starting dose is 25-50 mcg/day, with gradual increments every 6-8 weeks as needed, adjusting in 12.5-25 mcg increments until TSH levels normalize. For severe hypothyroidism, start at 12.5-25 mcg/day, increasing by 25 mcg every 2-4 weeks. For secondary or tertiary hypothyroidism, adjust until clinical euthyroidism and free T4 levels are normalized. Patients over 50 or with cardiac issues should take 1.7 mcg/kg/day.\r\nPediatric Dosing: For newborns, the starting dose is 10-15 mcg/kg/day, increasing as needed. In infants and children with chronic or severe hypothyroidism, the initial dose is 25 mcg/day with increments of 25 mcg every 2-4 weeks based on response. Doses for specific age groups vary and should be adjusted according to clinical and laboratory parameters.', 'what-is-the-recommended-dosage-for-levothyroxine', NULL, '2024-11-04 17:08:47', '2024-11-04 17:08:47'),
(194, '41', 'What drug interactions should be noted with Levothyroxine?', 'Concurrent use of tricyclic antidepressants and Levothyroxine may enhance both therapeutic and toxic effects, increasing the risk of cardiac arrhythmias and CNS stimulation. If Levothyroxine is added to antidiabetic therapy, monitoring is necessary as it may require increased dosages. Serum levels of digitalis glycosides may decrease in hyperthyroidism or when transitioning from hypothyroid to euthyroid states.', 'what-drug-interactions-should-be-noted-with-levothyroxine', NULL, '2024-11-04 17:09:06', '2024-11-04 17:09:06'),
(195, '41', 'What are the contraindications for Levothyroxine?', 'Levothyroxine is contraindicated in untreated thyrotoxicosis, acute myocardial infarction, and uncorrected adrenal failure.', 'what-are-the-contraindications-for-levothyroxine', NULL, '2024-11-04 17:09:25', '2024-11-04 17:09:25'),
(196, '41', 'What side effects are associated with Levothyroxine therapy?', 'Side effects primarily stem from hyperthyroidism due to overdose and may include fatigue, increased appetite, weight loss, heat intolerance, headaches, hyperactivity, nervousness, palpitations, tachycardia, gastrointestinal symptoms (e.g., diarrhea), and dermatologic reactions (e.g., hair loss).', 'what-side-effects-are-associated-with-levothyroxine-therapy', NULL, '2024-11-04 17:09:45', '2024-11-04 17:09:45'),
(197, '41', 'What should be considered regarding Levothyroxine use during pregnancy and lactation?', 'Levothyroxine is classified as Pregnancy Category A. Pregnancy may increase its requirements, and while thyroid hormones are minimally excreted in breast milk, caution is advised when administering it to nursing women to maintain normal lactation with adequate replacement doses.', 'what-should-be-considered-regarding-levothyroxine-use-during-pregnancy-and-lactation', NULL, '2024-11-04 17:10:04', '2024-11-04 17:10:04'),
(198, '41', 'What precautions should be taken when using Levothyroxine?', 'Caution is advised in patients with pituitary-related hypothyroidism, as adrenal insufficiency may also be present. Starting doses should be carefully adjusted in patients with cardiovascular disease or severe, long-standing hypothyroidism to avoid adverse effects. Significant changes in body weight during treatment require dosage adjustments, and TSH levels should be monitored to establish the correct dosages.', 'what-precautions-should-be-taken-when-using-levothyroxine', NULL, '2024-11-04 17:10:25', '2024-11-04 17:10:25'),
(199, '41', 'What are the effects of an overdose of Levothyroxine?', 'Overdose symptoms resemble hyperthyroidism and can include agitation, confusion, tachycardia, and severe complications such as cerebral embolism and shock. If overdose occurs, the dosage should be reduced or temporarily discontinued, and treatment should be symptomatic.', 'what-are-the-effects-of-an-overdose-of-levothyroxine', NULL, '2024-11-04 17:10:45', '2024-11-04 17:10:45'),
(200, '41', 'How should Levothyroxine be stored?', 'Store Levothyroxine below 30C in a dry place, protected from light, and keep out of reach of children.', 'how-should-levothyroxine-be-stored', NULL, '2024-11-04 17:11:05', '2024-11-04 17:11:05'),
(201, '42', 'What are the available strengths of Evania tablets?', 'Evania tablets are available in 10 mg and 25 mg strengths.', 'what-are-the-available-strengths-of-evania-tablets', NULL, '2024-11-04 17:57:28', '2024-11-04 17:57:28'),
(202, '42', 'What is Empagliflozin?', 'Empagliflozin is an orally active SGLT-2 receptor antagonist that promotes the excretion of excess glucose through the kidneys.', 'what-is-empagliflozin', NULL, '2024-11-04 17:57:48', '2024-11-04 17:57:48'),
(203, '42', 'What are the indications for Empagliflozin?', 'To improve glycemic control in adults with type 2 diabetes mellitus as an adjunct to diet and exercise. To reduce the risk of cardiovascular death in adults with type 2 diabetes and established cardiovascular disease.', 'what-are-the-indications-for-empagliflozin', NULL, '2024-11-04 17:58:12', '2024-11-04 17:58:12'),
(204, '42', 'What is the recommended dosage for Empagliflozin?', 'The starting dose is 10 mg once daily, which can be increased to 25 mg once daily. It can be taken with or without food.', 'what-is-the-recommended-dosage-for-empagliflozin', NULL, '2024-11-04 17:58:33', '2024-11-04 17:58:33'),
(205, '42', 'Who should not take Empagliflozin?', 'It is contraindicated in patients with a history of serious hypersensitivity to Empagliflozin, severe renal impairment, end-stage renal disease, or those on dialysis.', 'who-should-not-take-empagliflozin', NULL, '2024-11-04 17:58:57', '2024-11-04 17:58:57'),
(206, '42', 'What precautions should be taken when using Empagliflozin?', 'It should not be used in type 1 diabetes or diabetic ketoacidosis. Renal function should be assessed before initiation and periodically thereafter, and it should be discontinued if eGFR is persistently less than 45 ml/min/1.73 m.', 'what-precautions-should-be-taken-when-using-empagliflozin', NULL, '2024-11-04 17:59:18', '2024-11-04 17:59:18'),
(207, '42', 'What are common side effects of Empagliflozin?', 'Common side effects include low blood sugar (hypoglycemia) and urinary tract infections. Severe allergic reactions and dehydration are rare.', 'what-are-common-side-effects-of-empagliflozin', NULL, '2024-11-04 17:59:42', '2024-11-04 17:59:42'),
(208, '42', 'Is Empagliflozin safe during pregnancy and breastfeeding?', 'It should only be used if the benefits outweigh the risks during pregnancy. Its safety during breastfeeding is not established.', 'is-empagliflozin-safe-during-pregnancy-and-breastfeeding', NULL, '2024-11-04 18:00:03', '2024-11-04 18:00:03'),
(209, '42', 'Is Empagliflozin safe for children?', 'The safety and effectiveness in pediatric patients under 18 have not been established.', 'is-empagliflozin-safe-for-children', NULL, '2024-11-04 18:00:27', '2024-11-04 18:00:27'),
(210, '42', 'What drug interactions should be considered with Empagliflozin?', 'It may enhance the diuretic effects of thiazide and loop diuretics and increase the risk of hypoglycemia when used with insulin or insulin secretagogues.', 'what-drug-interactions-should-be-considered-with-empagliflozin', NULL, '2024-11-04 18:00:49', '2024-11-04 18:00:49'),
(211, '42', 'How should Evania tablets be stored?', 'Store at a temperature not exceeding 30C in a dry place, away from light and moisture.', 'how-should-evania-tablets-be-stored', NULL, '2024-11-04 18:01:16', '2024-11-04 18:01:16'),
(212, '63', 'What is Syndol?', 'Syndol is a medication designed to manage moderate to severe pain. It contains Tramadol Hydrochloride, an opioid analgesic that works on specific receptors in the brain to provide pain relief.', 'what-is-syndol', NULL, '2025-01-02 16:36:11', '2025-01-02 16:36:11'),
(213, '63', 'Who can use Syndol?', 'Syndol is suitable for adults and elderly patients. For those aged 65 to 75, no dosage adjustments are typically required unless they have kidney or liver problems. Children above one year may use the injection form, but other forms are not recommended for children under 12.', 'who-can-use-syndol', NULL, '2025-01-02 16:36:37', '2025-01-02 16:36:37'),
(214, '63', 'Who should not use Syndol?', 'Syndol should not be used by individuals allergic to Tramadol or its components, those intoxicated with alcohol or drugs, or patients with a history of opioid dependence. Pregnant women and nursing mothers should only use Syndol if specifically advised by a healthcare provider, as its safety in these situations is not fully established.', 'who-should-not-use-syndol', NULL, '2025-01-02 16:37:19', '2025-01-02 16:37:19'),
(215, '63', 'How is Syndol administered?', 'Syndol is available as capsules and injections. Capsules are taken orally, with doses ranging from 50 to 100 mg every 4-6 hours as needed, not exceeding 400 mg per day. Injections are administered intravenously, intramuscularly, or by infusion, with a maximum daily dose of 600 mg.', 'how-is-syndol-administered', NULL, '2025-01-02 16:37:43', '2025-01-02 16:37:43'),
(216, '63', 'What precautions should I take before using Syndol?', 'Inform your doctor if you have epilepsy, head injuries, or increased intracranial pressure. Avoid combining Syndol with alcohol or medications that depress the central nervous system, as this may lead to respiratory depression or excessive drowsiness.', 'what-precautions-should-i-take-before-using-syndol', NULL, '2025-01-02 16:38:14', '2025-01-02 16:38:14'),
(217, '63', 'What are the side effects of Syndol?', 'Common side effects include nausea, vomiting, constipation, drowsiness, and dizziness. Rarely, it may cause low blood pressure, hallucinations, or mood changes. Contact your healthcare provider if side effects persist or worsen.', 'what-are-the-side-effects-of-syndol', NULL, '2025-01-02 16:38:44', '2025-01-02 16:38:44'),
(218, '63', 'How should I store Syndol?', 'Syndol should be stored in a cool, dry place below 30C, away from light, moisture, and out of reach of children.', 'how-should-i-store-syndol', NULL, '2025-01-02 16:39:10', '2025-01-02 16:39:10'),
(219, '63', 'What should I do in case of an overdose?', 'If you suspect an overdose, seek medical attention immediately. Symptoms may include severe drowsiness, slow breathing, or loss of consciousness.', 'what-should-i-do-in-case-of-an-overdose', NULL, '2025-01-02 16:39:34', '2025-01-02 16:39:34'),
(220, '64', 'What is the composition of Clonatril Tablets?', 'Clonatril Tablets are available in three strengths:\r\nClonatril 0.5 mg Tablets (cross-scored): Contain clonazepam USP 0.5 mg per tablet.\r\nClonatril 1 mg Tablets (cross-scored): Contain clonazepam USP 1.0 mg per tablet.\r\nClonatril 2 mg Tablets (cross-scored): Contain clonazepam USP 2.0 mg per tablet.', '', NULL, '2025-01-06 09:30:04', '2025-01-06 09:34:58'),
(221, '64', 'What is the pharmacology of Clonatril?', 'Clonatril (clonazepam) belongs to the benzodiazepine class of drugs and exhibits sedative, hypnotic, and anticonvulsant properties. Its anticonvulsant effects are similar to other benzodiazepines.', 'what-is-the-pharmacology-of-clonatril', NULL, '2025-01-06 09:35:24', '2025-01-06 09:35:24'),
(222, '64', 'What are the indications for Clonatril use?', 'Clonatril is indicated for the treatment of:\r\nAnxiety and panic disorders, with or without agoraphobia.\r\nEpilepsy and other seizure disorders.', 'what-are-the-indications-for-clonatril-use', NULL, '2025-01-06 09:35:50', '2025-01-06 09:35:50'),
(223, '64', 'What is the dosage and administration for Clonatril?', 'The dosage should be individualized based on clinical response and tolerance:\r\nFor Epilepsy:\r\nInfants and children (10 years or 30 kg): Initial dose is 0.010.03 mg/kg daily, gradually increased to 0.050.1 mg/kg daily as a maintenance dose.\r\nChildren (>10 years or >30 kg): Initial dose is 12 mg daily, with a maintenance dose of 1.53 mg daily.\r\nAdults: Initial dose is 12 mg daily, increasing to a maintenance dose of 24 mg daily. The maximum therapeutic dose is 20 mg daily.\r\n\r\nFor Panic Disorder:\r\nStart with 0.250.5 mg twice daily, increasing by 0.250.5 mg every 35 days. The maintenance dose is 13 mg daily, though some patients may require up to 68 mg daily.\r\n\r\nGradual tapering of 0.250.5 mg weekly is necessary when discontinuing treatment.', 'what-is-the-dosage-and-administration-for-clonatril', NULL, '2025-01-06 09:36:38', '2025-01-06 09:36:38'),
(224, '64', 'Are there any restrictions on Clonatril use?', 'Yes, Clonatril is contraindicated in:\r\nPatients with hypersensitivity to clonazepam or its excipients.\r\nThose with myasthenia gravis or severe liver damage.\r\nIndividuals dependent on drugs or alcohol.\r\nPrecautions: Dosage adjustments are needed for elderly patients, those with respiratory, liver, or kidney conditions, and during concurrent use of centrally acting medications. Clonatril should only be used during pregnancy if the benefits outweigh the risks. It is contraindicated during breastfeeding unless nursing is discontinued.', 'are-there-any-restrictions-on-clonatril-use', NULL, '2025-01-06 09:37:09', '2025-01-06 09:37:09');
INSERT INTO `overviews` (`id`, `P_id`, `question`, `answare`, `slug`, `sequece`, `created_at`, `updated_at`) VALUES
(225, '64', 'Can Clonatril be taken with other medications?', 'Yes, Clonatril can be taken with other antiepileptic agents, but the dosages of all medications must be carefully adjusted to avoid sedation or apathy. Alcohol and other centrally acting medications (e.g., anesthetics, hypnotics) should not be used concurrently, as they may potentiate Clonatril\'s effects.', 'can-clonatril-be-taken-with-other-medications', NULL, '2025-01-06 09:37:32', '2025-01-06 09:37:32'),
(226, '64', 'What should be done in case of Clonatril overdose?', 'Symptoms of overdose include drowsiness, ataxia, stupor, and, in severe cases, coma with respiratory or circulatory collapse. Treatment involves supportive measures such as monitoring vital signs, gastric lavage, and intravenous fluid replacement. The benzodiazepine antagonist flumazenil (Anexate) is not recommended for patients with epilepsy, as it may provoke seizures.', 'what-should-be-done-in-case-of-clonatril-overdose', NULL, '2025-01-06 09:38:00', '2025-01-06 09:38:00'),
(227, '64', 'How should Clonatril be stored?', 'Clonatril should be stored at a temperature not exceeding 30C and protected from light. It should not be used beyond the expiry date printed on the packaging.', 'how-should-clonatril-be-stored', NULL, '2025-01-06 09:38:24', '2025-01-06 09:38:24'),
(228, '64', 'What are the available pack sizes for Clonatril?', 'Clonatril is available in the following pack sizes:\r\nClonatril 0.5 mg Tablets: 5x10 tablets in blister packs.\r\nClonatril 1 mg Tablets: 3x10 tablets in blister packs.\r\nClonatril 2 mg Tablets: 3x10 tablets in blister packs', 'what-are-the-available-pack-sizes-for-clonatril', NULL, '2025-01-06 09:38:53', '2025-01-06 09:38:53'),
(229, '50', 'What is the presentation of Delpark Tablets?', 'Delpark is available in two formulations: Delpark 2 mg tablets, where each film-coated tablet contains Trihexyphenidyl HCI BP 2 mg, and Delpark 5 mg tablets, where each film-coated tablet contains Trihexyphenidyl HCI BP 5 mg.', 'what-is-the-presentation-of-delpark-tablets', NULL, '2025-01-06 09:51:19', '2025-01-06 09:51:19'),
(230, '50', 'What are the indications for Delpark Tablets?', 'Delpark is indicated as an adjunct treatment for all forms of parkinsonism, including postencephalitic, arteriosclerotic, and idiopathic types. It is also used to manage extrapyramidal disorders caused by central nervous system drugs, such as dibenzoxazepines, phenothiazines, thioxanthenes, and butyrophenones, making it versatile in addressing both primary and drug-induced conditions.', 'what-are-the-indications-for-delpark-tablets', NULL, '2025-01-06 09:51:40', '2025-01-06 09:51:40'),
(231, '50', 'How should Delpark Tablets be administered?', 'The dosage of Delpark should be individualized. For idiopathic parkinsonism, therapy typically begins with 1 mg on the first day, increasing by 2 mg every three to five days until a daily dose of 6-10 mg is reached. In some cases, such as postencephalitic parkinsonism, patients may require higher doses, up to 12-15 mg daily. For drug-induced parkinsonism, the usual daily dose ranges from 5-15 mg, starting with 1 mg and adjusting as needed. When combined with levodopa, 3-6 mg of Trihexyphenidyl HCI daily, divided into doses, is usually sufficient. Doses exceeding 10 mg daily should be split into three doses taken with meals and one dose at bedtime to ensure effective absorption and minimize side effects.', 'how-should-delpark-tablets-be-administered', NULL, '2025-01-06 09:52:19', '2025-01-06 09:52:19'),
(232, '50', 'What are the contraindications for Delpark Tablets?', 'Delpark should not be used in individuals who are hypersensitive to Trihexyphenidyl HCI or those with narrow-angle glaucoma. This is particularly critical as long-term use of the medication has been associated with the risk of blindness in such cases.', 'what-are-the-contraindications-for-delpark-tablets', NULL, '2025-01-06 09:52:39', '2025-01-06 09:52:39'),
(233, '50', 'What precautions should be taken during therapy?', 'Patients should undergo an evaluation for narrow-angle glaucoma before starting treatment and have regular monitoring of intraocular pressure during therapy. Caution is necessary in hot environments, especially for those who are chronically ill, perform manual labor, or consume alcohol, as the drug may impair sweating, potentially leading to anhidrosis and hyperthermia. Additionally, abrupt withdrawal of the medication should be avoided to prevent Neuroleptic Malignant Syndrome (NMS) or worsening of parkinsonism symptoms.', 'what-precautions-should-be-taken-during-therapy', NULL, '2025-01-06 09:52:58', '2025-01-06 09:52:58'),
(234, '50', 'Can Delpark Tablets be used during pregnancy or lactation?', 'The safety of Trihexyphenidyl HCI during pregnancy or lactation is not well established, and its use should be limited to situations where the benefits clearly outweigh the risks. It may suppress milk production, and its effects on nursing infants are not fully understood.', 'can-delpark-tablets-be-used-during-pregnancy-or-lactation', NULL, '2025-01-06 09:53:17', '2025-01-06 09:53:17'),
(235, '50', 'Are there any drug interactions with Delpark Tablets?', 'Trihexyphenidyl HCI may interact with cannabinoids, barbiturates, opiates, and alcohol, enhancing sedative effects. Concurrent use with monoamine oxidase inhibitors or tricyclic antidepressants may increase anticholinergic effects. When used alongside neuroleptics, there is an increased risk of tardive dyskinesia. Dosage adjustments may be necessary during combination therapy with levodopa or other medications.', 'are-there-any-drug-interactions-with-delpark-tablets', NULL, '2025-01-06 09:53:38', '2025-01-06 09:53:38'),
(236, '50', 'What are the common side effects of Delpark Tablets?', 'Common side effects include dry mouth, blurred vision, dizziness, mild nausea, and nervousness, which may improve with continued use. Rarely, patients may experience suppurative parotitis, skin rashes, hallucinations, delusions, and paralytic ileus. Other side effects, such as constipation, urinary retention, tachycardia, and pupil dilation, have also been reported. Abrupt withdrawal of the medication can exacerbate parkinsonism symptoms or lead to Neuroleptic Malignant Syndrome.', 'what-are-the-common-side-effects-of-delpark-tablets', NULL, '2025-01-06 09:54:02', '2025-01-06 09:54:02'),
(237, '50', 'What happens in case of an overdose?', 'An overdose of Delpark may present symptoms similar to atropine intoxication, including dilated pupils, dry skin, tachycardia, and elevated temperature, along with neuropsychiatric symptoms like delirium and hallucinations. Treatment involves symptomatic and supportive care, including gastric lavage and respiratory support, as needed, to address the overdose effectively.', 'what-happens-in-case-of-an-overdose', NULL, '2025-01-06 09:54:24', '2025-01-06 09:54:24'),
(238, '50', 'How should Delpark Tablets be stored?', 'Delpark should be stored in a dry place at temperatures not exceeding 30C, away from light, to maintain its stability and efficacy over time.', 'how-should-delpark-tablets-be-stored', NULL, '2025-01-06 09:54:45', '2025-01-06 09:54:45'),
(239, '51', 'What is the pharmacology of Leptal?', 'The pharmacological action of Leptal (Oxcarbazepine) is primarily mediated through its active 10-monohydroxy metabolite (MHD). Although the exact mechanism of action is not fully understood, studies suggest that Oxcarbazepine and MHD block voltage-sensitive sodium channels. This helps stabilize hyperexcited neural membranes, inhibiting repetitive neuronal firing and reducing synaptic impulse propagation, all of which contribute to preventing seizures. Additionally, Oxcarbazepine may increase potassium conductance and modulate high-voltage-activated calcium channels, enhancing its anticonvulsant effects. It does not show significant interactions with brain neurotransmitter or modulator receptor sites.', 'what-is-the-pharmacology-of-leptal', NULL, '2025-01-06 10:28:53', '2025-01-06 10:28:53'),
(240, '51', 'What are the indications for Leptal?', 'Leptal is indicated for the treatment of partial seizures. In adults, it can be used both as monotherapy or adjunctive therapy. In pediatric patients, it is indicated as monotherapy for partial seizures in children aged 4 to 16 years, and as adjunctive therapy for children aged 2 to 16 years.', 'what-are-the-indications-for-leptal', NULL, '2025-01-06 10:29:16', '2025-01-06 10:29:16'),
(241, '51', 'How is Leptal administered?', 'For adults, the initial dose is 600 mg per day, divided into two doses. If used as adjunctive therapy, the dose can be increased by 600 mg every week, with a typical maintenance dose of 1200 mg per day. For monotherapy conversion, the drug is gradually increased over 3 to 6 weeks to a maximum of 2400 mg per day. For patients with renal impairment, a lower starting dose is recommended. In pediatric patients, the initial dose ranges from 810 mg/kg/day, with adjustments made every few weeks to achieve the desired therapeutic effect. The maximum dose for children under 4 years should not exceed 60 mg/kg/day.', 'how-is-leptal-administered', NULL, '2025-01-06 10:29:35', '2025-01-06 10:29:35'),
(242, '51', 'What are the contraindications for Leptal?', 'Leptal is contraindicated in patients who have a known hypersensitivity to Oxcarbazepine or any of its components, including eslicarbazepine acetate.', 'what-are-the-contraindications-for-leptal', NULL, '2025-01-06 10:30:11', '2025-01-06 10:30:11'),
(243, '51', 'What precautions should be taken during the use of Leptal?', 'Patients using Leptal should be monitored for cognitive and neuropsychiatric events such as psychomotor slowing, difficulty concentrating, and somnolence. Special caution should be exercised regarding hyponatremia, with regular monitoring of serum sodium levels, especially in patients on medications that affect sodium levels. Patients with a hypersensitivity reaction to carbamazepine should also use this medication with caution.', 'what-precautions-should-be-taken-during-the-use-of-leptal', NULL, '2025-01-06 10:30:28', '2025-01-06 10:30:28'),
(244, '51', 'What are the common adverse effects of Leptal?', 'Common side effects of Leptal include dizziness, diplopia (double vision), headache, nystagmus, and abnormal gait. Gastrointestinal issues like nausea, vomiting, and abdominal pain may also occur. Dermatologic reactions such as rash are possible, and hyponatremia can also develop. Rare side effects include bone marrow suppression and hepatotoxicity.', 'what-are-the-common-adverse-effects-of-leptal', NULL, '2025-01-06 10:30:49', '2025-01-06 10:30:49'),
(245, '51', 'Are there any drug interactions with Leptal?', 'Leptal exhibits minimal interaction with cytochrome P450 enzymes, meaning it has fewer interactions with other medications. There are no significant interactions reported with drugs such as cimetidine, dextropropoxyphene, erythromycin, or warfarin. However, due to its adjunctive use with other antiepileptics, careful monitoring is advised for potential effects on other anticonvulsants.', 'are-there-any-drug-interactions-with-leptal', NULL, '2025-01-06 10:31:06', '2025-01-06 10:31:06'),
(246, '51', 'What is the safety of Leptal during pregnancy and lactation?', 'Leptal is classified as a Category C drug during pregnancy, meaning there are no well-controlled studies available. It should only be used during pregnancy if the potential benefits outweigh the risks. Since Oxcarbazepine is excreted in human milk, it is not recommended for use during breastfeeding.', 'what-is-the-safety-of-leptal-during-pregnancy-and-lactation', NULL, '2025-01-06 10:31:25', '2025-01-06 10:31:25'),
(247, '51', 'How should Leptal be stored?', 'Leptal should be stored at temperatures not exceeding 30C in a dry place, protected from light and moisture to maintain its efficacy.', 'how-should-leptal-be-stored', NULL, '2025-01-06 10:31:41', '2025-01-06 10:31:41'),
(248, '51', 'How is Leptal supplied?', 'Leptal is available in two formulations: 300 mg tablets (3 x 10 tablets in Alu-PVDC blister packs) and 600 mg tablets (2 x 10 tablets in Alu-PVDC blister packs).', 'how-is-leptal-supplied', NULL, '2025-01-06 10:31:58', '2025-01-06 10:31:58'),
(249, '52', 'What is the pharmacology of Pregabalin?', 'Pregabalin is a structural derivative of gamma-amino-butyric acid (GABA), but it does not bind to GABAA, GABAB, or benzodiazepine receptors. Instead, it binds with high affinity to the alpha 2-delta site, which is an auxiliary subunit of voltage-gated calcium channels in the central nervous system. This binding reduces calcium influx into nerve terminals, which results in the inhibition of excitatory neurotransmitter release. Pregabalin has a 90% oral bioavailability and is mainly excreted via the kidneys. Its elimination half-life is approximately 6 hours, and it can be taken with or without food.', 'what-is-the-pharmacology-of-pregabalin', NULL, '2025-01-06 10:43:54', '2025-01-06 10:43:54'),
(250, '52', 'What are the indications and uses of Pregabalin?', 'Pregabalin is indicated for several conditions:\r\n\r\nNeuralgia: It is used to treat pain from diabetic neuropathy and post-herpetic neuralgia.\r\nPartial Seizures / Epilepsy: It serves as adjunctive therapy for adult patients with partial onset seizures.', 'what-are-the-indications-and-uses-of-pregabalin', NULL, '2025-01-06 10:44:14', '2025-01-06 10:44:14'),
(251, '52', 'What are the contraindications for Pregabalin?', 'Pregabalin is contraindicated in patients who have a known hypersensitivity to the drug.', 'what-are-the-contraindications-for-pregabalin', NULL, '2025-01-06 10:44:33', '2025-01-06 10:44:33'),
(252, '52', 'How is Pregabalin dosed and administered?', 'Diabetic Neuropathic Pain: The initial dose is 50 mg three times a day, which can be increased to a maximum of 300 mg/day within 1 week, depending on efficacy and tolerability, in patients with a creatinine clearance of at least 60 mL/min.\r\nPost-Herpetic Neuralgia: The recommended dose is between 75 and 150 mg twice a day, or 50 to 100 mg three times a day, for patients with a creatinine clearance of at least 60 mL/min. The dose may be increased to 300 mg/day within 1 week.\r\nEpilepsy: The typical dose for partial onset seizures is between 150 and 600 mg/day, as adjunctive therapy for adults.', 'how-is-pregabalin-dosed-and-administered', NULL, '2025-01-06 10:44:56', '2025-01-06 10:44:56'),
(253, '52', 'What precautions should be taken with Pregabalin?', 'Pregabalin should not be abruptly discontinued, as rapid withdrawal may cause symptoms such as insomnia, nausea, headache, and diarrhea. A gradual tapering over at least 1 week is recommended. Additionally, Pregabalin can cause an elevation in creatine kinase levels, and if myopathy is suspected or significant increases in creatine kinase are noted, the drug should be discontinued.', 'what-precautions-should-be-taken-with-pregabalin', NULL, '2025-01-06 10:45:15', '2025-01-06 10:45:15'),
(254, '52', 'What are the side effects of Pregabalin?', 'Pregabalin is generally well tolerated, but some common side effects include:\r\n\r\nCentral Nervous System: Dizziness, somnolence (drowsiness), and blurred vision.', 'what-are-the-side-effects-of-pregabalin', NULL, '2025-01-06 10:45:37', '2025-01-06 10:45:37'),
(255, '52', 'What are the recommendations for using Pregabalin during pregnancy and lactation?', 'Pregnancy: Pregabalin is classified as a Category C drug for pregnancy, meaning there are no well-controlled studies in pregnant women. It should be used only when the potential benefits justify the risks to the fetus.\r\nLactation: Pregabalin may be excreted in breast milk, and its use during breastfeeding should only occur if the potential benefits outweigh the risks.', 'what-are-the-recommendations-for-using-pregabalin-during-pregnancy-and-lactation', NULL, '2025-01-06 10:45:57', '2025-01-06 10:45:57'),
(256, '52', 'Is Pregabalin safe for pediatric use?', 'The safety and efficacy of Pregabalin in pediatric patients have not been established, and it should not be used in this population unless specifically indicated.', 'is-pregabalin-safe-for-pediatric-use', NULL, '2025-01-06 10:46:15', '2025-01-06 10:46:15'),
(257, '52', 'What are the signs of Pregabalin overdose?', 'Overdose symptoms include dizziness, somnolence, blurred vision, and mild diarrhea. In cases of overdose, Pregabalin can be removed by emesis or gastric lavage if necessary.', 'what-are-the-signs-of-pregabalin-overdose', NULL, '2025-01-06 10:46:32', '2025-01-06 10:46:32'),
(258, '53', 'What is the pharmacology of Rasagil?', 'Rasagiline is an irreversible monoamine oxidase B (MAO-B) inhibitor primarily used to treat Parkinson\'s disease (PD). By inhibiting MAO-B, Rasagiline increases the extracellular levels of dopamine in the striatum, leading to enhanced dopaminergic activity. This increase in dopaminergic function helps to alleviate the symptoms of dopaminergic motor dysfunction, which is common in PD.', 'what-is-the-pharmacology-of-rasagil', NULL, '2025-01-06 10:56:03', '2025-01-06 10:56:03'),
(259, '53', 'What are the indications and uses of Rasagil?', 'Rasagil is indicated for:\r\nMonotherapy or Adjunct Therapy in the treatment of Parkinsons disease (PD), either alone or in combination with levodopa.', 'what-are-the-indications-and-uses-of-rasagil', NULL, '2025-01-06 10:56:22', '2025-01-06 10:56:22'),
(260, '53', 'How should Rasagil be dosed and administered?', 'Monotherapy or Adjunct Therapy (no levodopa): The recommended dose is 1 mg taken orally once daily.\r\nPatients on levodopa: Start with 0.5 mg orally once daily. If well tolerated but there is insufficient clinical response, the dose may be increased to 1 mg once daily. In some cases, a reduction in levodopa dosage may be considered based on individual patient response. The maximum recommended dose is 1 mg once daily due to the risk of hypertension.', 'how-should-rasagil-be-dosed-and-administered', NULL, '2025-01-06 10:56:42', '2025-01-06 10:56:42'),
(261, '53', 'What are the contraindications and precautions for Rasagil?', 'Hypertension: Rasagil may exacerbate hypertension. If sustained, adjustments in medication may be necessary.\r\nTyramine-rich foods: These should be avoided as they can lead to severe hypertension due to tyramine interactions, particularly with high intake levels.\r\nSerotonin Syndrome: This condition can occur when Rasagil is combined with certain antidepressants (SSRIs, SNRIs, tricyclics, tetracyclics) or nonselective MAOIs (e.g., phenelzine, tranylcypromine).\r\nCiprofloxacin or other CYP1A2 Inhibitors: Patients taking these should not exceed 0.5 mg of Rasagil daily.\r\nHepatic Impairment: In patients with mild hepatic impairment, the dose should be reduced to 0.5 mg once daily. Rasagil is contraindicated in patients with moderate or severe hepatic impairment.\r\nConcomitant Medications: Rasagil should not be used with fluoxetine or fluvoxamine, and there should be a washout period before and after use with these drugs. Additionally, combinations with dextromethorphan, sympathomimetics, or certain other drugs should be avoided.\r\nMelanoma Risk: There have been reports of melanoma; however, the increased risk is more likely related to Parkinson\'s disease than to Rasagil itself.', 'what-are-the-contraindications-and-precautions-for-rasagil', NULL, '2025-01-06 10:57:02', '2025-01-06 10:57:02'),
(262, '53', 'What are the drug interactions with Rasagil?', 'Detailed drug interactions can be found in the Contraindications & Precautions section, which includes interactions with antidepressants, antihypertensive medications, and other drugs that influence serotonin levels or the CYP450 enzyme system.', 'what-are-the-drug-interactions-with-rasagil', NULL, '2025-01-06 10:57:20', '2025-01-06 10:57:20'),
(263, '53', 'What are the side effects of Rasagil?', 'Common side effects may include:\r\nCentral Nervous System: Joint pain, mild headache, dizziness, and spinning sensations.\r\nDermatologic: Mild skin rash, hair loss.\r\nGastrointestinal: Dry mouth, constipation, diarrhea, stomach upset, and vomiting.\r\nOther: Loss of appetite, weight loss, numbness, or tingling sensation.', 'what-are-the-side-effects-of-rasagil', NULL, '2025-01-06 10:57:40', '2025-01-06 10:57:40'),
(264, '53', 'What are the considerations for use in pregnancy and lactation?', 'Pregnancy: Rasagil is classified as Pregnancy Category C, meaning there are no well-controlled studies in pregnant women. It should only be used if the benefits outweigh the risks to the fetus.\r\nLactation: It is unknown whether Rasagil is excreted in breast milk. Caution is advised when using it during breastfeeding.', 'what-are-the-considerations-for-use-in-pregnancy-and-lactation', NULL, '2025-01-06 10:58:00', '2025-01-06 10:58:00'),
(265, '53', 'Is Rasagil safe for pediatric use?', 'The safety and effectiveness of Rasagil in pediatric patients have not been established, so it is not recommended for use in children.', 'is-rasagil-safe-for-pediatric-use', NULL, '2025-01-06 10:58:24', '2025-01-06 10:58:24'),
(266, '53', 'How should Rasagil be stored?', 'Store Rasagil at temperatures not exceeding 30C in a dry place, and protect it from light.', 'how-should-rasagil-be-stored', NULL, '2025-01-06 10:58:41', '2025-01-06 10:58:41'),
(267, '53', 'What happens in case of an overdose?', 'Signs of overdose may include drowsiness, dizziness, irritability, agitation, severe headache, hallucinations, trismus, convulsions, and coma. Other symptoms could include rapid and irregular pulse, hypertension, hypotension, vascular collapse, and respiratory issues. There is no specific antidote for Rasagil overdose, and management involves providing respiratory support, monitoring body temperature, and managing hyperpyrexia. Patients should follow dietary tyramine restrictions for several weeks after an overdose.', 'what-happens-in-case-of-an-overdose', NULL, '2025-01-06 10:59:02', '2025-01-06 10:59:02'),
(268, '54', 'What is Synamet used for?', 'Synamet tablets are primarily indicated for the treatment of Parkinson\'s disease and Parkinson\'s syndrome. It is effective in relieving many symptoms of parkinsonism, particularly rigidity and bradykinesia. It is also useful for managing tremors, dysphagia (difficulty swallowing), sialorrhea (excessive salivation), and postural instability associated with Parkinsons disease. Additionally, it can enhance motor recovery after a stroke when combined with physiotherapy.', 'what-is-synamet-used-for', NULL, '2025-01-06 11:15:56', '2025-01-06 11:15:56'),
(269, '54', 'What is the pharmacology of Synamet?', 'Synamet contains two active ingredients:\r\nLevodopa: This is the metabolic precursor of dopamine, which crosses the blood-brain barrier and is converted into dopamine in the brain.\r\nCarbidopa: This is a dopa decarboxylase inhibitor, which prevents the peripheral metabolism of levodopa into dopamine. This allows more levodopa to reach the brain, thus improving therapeutic efficacy.', 'what-is-the-pharmacology-of-synamet', NULL, '2025-01-06 11:16:16', '2025-01-06 11:16:16'),
(270, '54', 'How is Synamet dosed and administered?', 'For the 100/10 mg tablet:\r\nThe initial dosage is typically one tablet 34 times a day.\r\nThe dose may be increased by one tablet daily or every other day until a total of eight tablets (two tablets four times a day) is reached.\r\nFor the 250/25 mg tablet:\r\nBegin with half a tablet taken once or twice a day. This may not provide the optimal amount of carbidopa for some patients.\r\nGradually increase the dosage by adding one-half tablet every day or every other day until the optimal response is achieved.\r\nFor patients needing more than 1500 mg of levodopa daily, one tablet of 250/25 mg can be taken 34 times daily.\r\nThe maintenance dose should be individualized according to the therapeutic response. The dosage can be adjusted, but the maximum recommended dosage is eight tablets per day.', 'how-is-synamet-dosed-and-administered', NULL, '2025-01-06 11:16:47', '2025-01-06 11:16:47'),
(271, '54', 'What are the contraindications for Synamet?', 'Synamet should not be used in:\r\nPatients with hypersensitivity to carbidopa or levodopa.\r\nPatients with narrow-angle glaucoma.\r\nIndividuals with suspicious undiagnosed skin lesions or a history of melanoma, as levodopa can activate malignant melanoma.', 'what-are-the-contraindications-for-synamet', NULL, '2025-01-06 11:17:10', '2025-01-06 11:17:10'),
(272, '54', 'What are the potential side effects of Synamet?', 'Common side effects due to the central neuropharmacologic activity of dopamine include:\r\nCentral Nervous System: Dyskinesias (involuntary movements), nausea, dizziness, somnolence (sleepiness), delusions, hallucinations, depression, and confusion.\r\nCardiovascular: Orthostatic hypotension (low blood pressure when standing), chest pain, palpitations, and hypertension.\r\nGastrointestinal: Vomiting, gastrointestinal bleeding, duodenal ulcers, diarrhea, and dark saliva.\r\nHematologic: Leukopenia (low white blood cell count), anemia, thrombocytopenia (low platelet count), and agranulocytosis (severe reduction in white blood cells).\r\nHypersensitivity: Angioedema, urticaria (hives), and pruritus (itching).\r\nSkin: Alopecia (hair loss), rash, and dark sweat.\r\nUrogenital: Dark urine.\r\nRespiratory: Dyspnea (shortness of breath).', 'what-are-the-potential-side-effects-of-synamet', NULL, '2025-01-06 11:17:33', '2025-01-06 11:17:33'),
(273, '54', 'What are the warnings and precautions for Synamet?', 'Psychiatric Effects: Careful observation is required for depression and suicidal tendencies. Patients with a history of psychosis should be treated with caution.\r\nCardiovascular Effects: Caution should be exercised in patients with severe cardiovascular or pulmonary disease, and cardiac function should be monitored closely during the initial dosage titration.\r\nUse in Glaucoma: It should be used cautiously in patients with chronic wide-angle glaucoma, but only if intraocular pressure is well-controlled and the patient is monitored for changes.\r\nExtrapyramidal Reactions: Carbidopa-Levodopa is not recommended for treating drug-induced extrapyramidal symptoms.\r\nOther Conditions: Use cautiously in patients with a history of peptic ulcers, convulsions, renal, hepatic, or endocrine disorders.', 'what-are-the-warnings-and-precautions-for-synamet', NULL, '2025-01-06 11:17:54', '2025-01-06 11:17:54'),
(274, '54', 'What are the drug interactions with Synamet?', 'Antihypertensive medications: Symptomatic postural hypotension can occur when carbidopa-levodopa is added to antihypertensive therapy, requiring potential dose adjustments.\r\nTricyclic antidepressants: Rarely, these can cause hypertension and dyskinesia when used with carbidopa-levodopa.\r\nIron supplements: Ferrous sulfate or ferrous gluconate may reduce the bioavailability of levodopa.\r\nDopamine antagonists: Medications like phenothiazines, risperidone, and isoniazid may reduce the effectiveness of levodopa.\r\nOther interactions: Phenytoin and papaverine may reverse the effects of levodopa.', 'what-are-the-drug-interactions-with-synamet', NULL, '2025-01-06 11:18:13', '2025-01-06 11:18:13'),
(275, '54', 'What is the use of Synamet during pregnancy and lactation?', 'Pregnancy: Carbidopa-Levodopa should be used during pregnancy only if the benefits outweigh the potential risks, as both levodopa and its combinations have caused malformations in animal studies.\r\nLactation: It is unknown whether carbidopa is excreted in breast milk. Because many drugs are excreted in milk and may cause adverse reactions in infants, a decision should be made to either discontinue nursing or discontinue carbidopa-levodopa, depending on the medicine\'s importance to the mother.', 'what-is-the-use-of-synamet-during-pregnancy-and-lactation', NULL, '2025-01-06 11:18:34', '2025-01-06 11:18:34'),
(276, '54', 'What are the storage conditions for Synamet?', 'Store in a cool, dry place, away from light.', 'what-are-the-storage-conditions-for-synamet', NULL, '2025-01-06 11:18:52', '2025-01-06 11:18:52'),
(277, '54', 'What are the special populations for Synamet use?', 'Children: The safety and effectiveness of Synamet in children under 18 have not been established, so its use is not recommended in this age group.\r\nPlease consult with a registered healthcare provider for individualized treatment advice.', 'what-are-the-special-populations-for-synamet-use', NULL, '2025-01-06 11:19:15', '2025-01-06 11:19:15'),
(278, '65', 'What is Anulid used for?', 'Anulid is used for the treatment of the following conditions:\r\n\r\nVancomycin-resistant Enterococcus faecium infections, including those with bacteremia.\r\nNosocomial pneumonia caused by Staphylococcus aureus (both methicillin-susceptible and -resistant strains) or Streptococcus pneumoniae (including multi-drug resistant strains).\r\nComplicated skin and skin structure infections (including diabetic foot infections without osteomyelitis) caused by Staphylococcus aureus (methicillin-susceptible and methicillin-resistant strains), Streptococcus pyogenes, or Streptococcus agalactiae.\r\nUncomplicated skin and skin structure infections caused by Staphylococcus aureus (methicillin-susceptible only) or Streptococcus pyogenes.\r\nCommunity-acquired pneumonia caused by Streptococcus pneumoniae (including multi-drug resistant strains) or Staphylococcus aureus (methicillin-susceptible strains).', 'what-is-anulid-used-for', NULL, '2025-01-06 12:43:22', '2025-01-06 12:43:22'),
(279, '65', 'What is the composition of Anulid?', 'Anulid Tablet 400 mg: Each film-coated tablet contains 400 mg of Linezolid.\r\nAnulid Tablet 600 mg: Each film-coated tablet contains 600 mg of Linezolid.\r\nAnulid Powder for Suspension: After reconstitution, each 5 mL contains 100 mg of Linezolid.', 'what-is-the-composition-of-anulid', NULL, '2025-01-06 12:43:46', '2025-01-06 12:43:46'),
(280, '65', 'How does Anulid work?', 'Linezolid is an antibacterial agent from the oxazolidinone class. It works by inhibiting bacterial protein synthesis by binding to the 23S ribosomal RNA of the bacterial ribosome, preventing the formation of a functional 70S initiation complex. This makes it bacteriostatic for enterococci and staphylococci and bactericidal for most streptococci.', 'how-does-anulid-work', NULL, '2025-01-06 12:44:06', '2025-01-06 12:44:06'),
(281, '65', 'What is the recommended dosage for Anulid?', 'Parenteral to Oral Switch: Can switch from parenteral to oral formulation when clinically appropriate as Linezolid has 100% oral bioavailability.\r\nInjection: Administered over 30-120 minutes.\r\nOral Tablet/Suspension: Can be taken with or without food.\r\nOral Suspension Reconstitution: Add 65 mL of boiled and cooled water in two portions to the suspension bottle. Shake well after each addition. Use within 21 days and store in a cool, dry place. Shake well before each use.', 'what-is-the-recommended-dosage-for-anulid', NULL, '2025-01-06 12:44:36', '2025-01-06 12:44:36'),
(282, '65', 'Who should not take Anulid?', 'Anulid is contraindicated in:\r\nIndividuals with known hypersensitivity to Linezolid or any component of the formulation.\r\nPatients on monoamine oxidase inhibitors (e.g., Phenelzine, Isocarboxazid) or within two weeks of stopping them.\r\nNot recommended for patients with uncontrolled hypertension, pheochromocytoma, thyrotoxicosis, carcinoid syndrome, or those taking sympathomimetic agents, vasopressors, dopaminergic agents, serotonin reuptake inhibitors, tricyclic antidepressants, serotonin 5-HT1 receptor agonists, meperidine, or buspirone.', 'who-should-not-take-anulid', NULL, '2025-01-06 12:45:02', '2025-01-06 12:45:02'),
(283, '65', 'Are there any warnings or precautions with Anulid?', 'Serotonin Syndrome: Linezolid can interact with serotonergic agents, leading to serotonin syndrome. Monitor for cognitive dysfunction, hyperreflexia, hyperpyrexia, and incoordination.\r\nVisual Changes: Prompt ophthalmic evaluation if visual changes occur.\r\nSeizures: Convulsions may occur, especially in patients with a history of seizures or other risk factors.\r\nNausea & Vomiting: Monitor for recurrent nausea, vomiting, acidosis, or low bicarbonate during treatment.', 'are-there-any-warnings-or-precautions-with-anulid', NULL, '2025-01-06 12:45:29', '2025-01-06 12:45:29'),
(284, '65', 'Can Anulid be used during pregnancy and breastfeeding?', 'Pregnancy: Category C. Should only be used if the benefits justify the risks to the fetus.\r\nBreastfeeding: The safety of Linezolid during breastfeeding is not known, so it should be used with caution.', 'can-anulid-be-used-during-pregnancy-and-breastfeeding', NULL, '2025-01-06 12:45:53', '2025-01-06 12:45:53'),
(285, '65', 'What drug interactions should be monitored when using Anulid?', 'Monoamine Oxidase Inhibition: Linezolid is a reversible, nonselective MAO inhibitor and can interact with adrenergic and serotonergic agents.\r\nAdrenergic Agents: May enhance the pressor response to indirect sympathomimetic agents.\r\nSerotonergic Agents: Be cautious of serotonin syndrome when used concurrently with serotonergic drugs.', 'what-drug-interactions-should-be-monitored-when-using-anulid', NULL, '2025-01-06 12:46:16', '2025-01-06 12:46:16'),
(286, '65', 'What should be done in case of overdose?', 'No specific cases of overdose have been reported.\r\nSupportive care is recommended.\r\nApproximately 30% of Linezolid is removed by haemodialysis over 3 hours.', 'what-should-be-done-in-case-of-overdose', NULL, '2025-01-06 12:46:54', '2025-01-06 12:46:54'),
(287, '65', 'How should Anulid be stored?', 'Store below 30C, in a dry place, away from light and moisture.\r\nKeep the product out of the reach of children.', 'how-should-anulid-be-stored', NULL, '2025-01-06 12:47:16', '2025-01-06 12:47:16'),
(288, '66', 'What drug interactions should be considered when using Denvar (Cefixime)?', 'In common with other cephalosporins, Denvar has been associated with increases in prothrombin time in a few patients. Extra care is required when administering Denvar to patients receiving anticoagulant therapy.', 'what-drug-interactions-should-be-considered-when-using-denvar-cefixime', NULL, '2025-01-06 13:03:50', '2025-01-06 13:03:50'),
(289, '66', 'What are the contraindications for Denvar?', 'Denvar is contraindicated in patients who are known to have hypersensitivity to cephalosporin antibiotics. It should not be administered to individuals with such known allergies.', 'what-are-the-contraindications-for-denvar', NULL, '2025-01-06 13:04:12', '2025-01-06 13:04:12'),
(290, '66', 'What side effects can be expected from Denvar?', 'Denvar is generally well tolerated, with most adverse effects being mild and self-limiting. Common gastrointestinal side effects include diarrhea, stool changes, nausea, abdominal pain, dyspepsia, vomiting, and flatulence. More serious effects like pseudomembranous colitis have been reported. Other less frequent side effects include headache, dizziness, rash, pruritis (itching), and urticaria (hives). Hematological changes like thrombocytopenia, leukopenia, and eosinophilia, though infrequent, may occur and are usually reversible.', 'what-side-effects-can-be-expected-from-denvar', NULL, '2025-01-06 13:04:47', '2025-01-06 13:04:47'),
(291, '66', 'Can Denvar be used during pregnancy and lactation?', 'There are no well-controlled studies of Denvar in pregnant women. Animal reproduction studies may not always predict human response, so Denvar should only be used during pregnancy if absolutely necessary. It is unknown whether Cefixime is excreted in human breast milk; therefore, caution should be exercised if Denvar is given to nursing mothers.', 'can-denvar-be-used-during-pregnancy-and-lactation', NULL, '2025-01-06 13:05:10', '2025-01-06 13:05:10'),
(292, '66', 'What precautions should be taken when prescribing Denvar?', 'Denvar should be prescribed with caution in patients who have previously shown hypersensitivity to drugs, particularly cephalosporins and penicillins, as partial cross-allergenicity exists between these drugs. Severe allergic reactions, including anaphylaxis, have been reported with both penicillins and cephalosporins. Denvar should also be used cautiously in patients with impaired renal function. Additionally, broad-spectrum antibiotic use can alter the normal flora of the colon, potentially leading to antibiotic-associated diarrhea caused by Clostridium difficile.', 'what-precautions-should-be-taken-when-prescribing-denvar', NULL, '2025-01-06 13:05:41', '2025-01-06 13:05:41'),
(293, '66', 'What should be done in the case of an overdose of Denvar?', 'In case of overdose, gastric lavage may be recommended, although there is no specific antidote for Denvar. Cefixime is not significantly removed from circulation by hemodialysis or peritoneal dialysis. In studies, healthy adult volunteers who received up to 2 g of Denvar in a single dose did not experience adverse reactions different from those seen at recommended doses.', 'what-should-be-done-in-the-case-of-an-overdose-of-denvar', NULL, '2025-01-06 13:06:08', '2025-01-06 13:06:08'),
(294, '66', 'What class of antibiotics does Denvar belong to?', 'Denvar is classified as a third-generation cephalosporin.', 'what-class-of-antibiotics-does-denvar-belong-to', NULL, '2025-01-06 13:06:43', '2025-01-06 13:06:43'),
(295, '66', 'How should Denvar be stored?', 'Denvar should be stored below 30C, protected from light and moisture. It should be kept out of the reach of children.', 'how-should-denvar-be-stored', NULL, '2025-01-06 13:07:05', '2025-01-06 13:07:05'),
(296, '67', 'What are the indications for Cefuroxime (Furotil)?', 'Cefuroxime is indicated for the treatment of infections caused by bacteria sensitive to this antibiotic. It is effective for conditions like:\r\n\r\nPharyngitis/Tonsillitis caused by Streptococcus pyogenes.\r\nAcute bacterial otitis media caused by Streptococcus pneumoniae, Haemophilus influenzae, Moraxella catarrhalis, or Streptococcus pyogenes.\r\nAcute bacterial maxillary sinusitis caused by Streptococcus pneumoniae or Haemophilus influenzae.\r\nLower respiratory tract infections (including pneumonia) caused by various bacteria like Streptococcus pneumoniae, Haemophilus influenzae, Klebsiella spp., and Staphylococcus aureus.\r\nAcute bacterial exacerbation of chronic bronchitis and secondary bacterial infections of acute bronchitis.\r\nSkin and skin-structure infections caused by Staphylococcus aureus or Streptococcus pyogenes.\r\nUrinary tract infections caused by E. coli or Klebsiella pneumoniae.\r\nBone and joint infections caused by Staphylococcus aureus.\r\nGonorrhea caused by Neisseria gonorrhoeae.\r\nEarly Lyme disease (erythema migrans) caused by Borrelia burgdorferi.', 'what-are-the-indications-for-cefuroxime-furotil', NULL, '2025-01-06 13:46:09', '2025-01-06 13:46:09'),
(297, '67', 'What is the pharmacological action of Cefuroxime (Furotil)?', 'Cefuroxime is a well-characterized and effective antibacterial agent with broad-spectrum bactericidal activity. It is stable against bacterial -lactamase, making it effective against many ampicillin- and amoxicillin-resistant strains.', 'what-is-the-pharmacological-action-of-cefuroxime-furotil', NULL, '2025-01-06 13:46:32', '2025-01-06 13:46:32'),
(298, '67', 'What is the recommended dosage for Cefuroxime (Furotil)?', 'Dosage varies based on the infection and age group:\r\n\r\nAdults (13+ years): For most conditions like pharyngitis, bronchitis, and pneumonia, the dosage ranges from 250 mg to 500 mg twice daily for 5-14 days. For uncomplicated gonorrhea, a single 1000 mg dose is given.\r\nPediatric Patients (3 months to 12 years): The dosage typically ranges from 20 mg/kg/day to 30 mg/kg/day in two divided doses for 5-10 days.\r\nParenteral Use (Adults and Children): The dose can range from 750 mg to 1.5 g via intramuscular or intravenous injection, depending on the severity of the infection.', 'what-is-the-recommended-dosage-for-cefuroxime-furotil', NULL, '2025-01-06 13:46:56', '2025-01-06 13:46:56'),
(299, '67', 'What side effects may occur with Cefuroxime (Furotil)?', 'Side effects are generally infrequent and mild, including:\r\n\r\nGastrointestinal disturbances like diarrhea and nausea.\r\nSkin rashes and hypersensitivity reactions. Prolonged use may result in the overgrowth of non-susceptible organisms like Candida.', 'what-side-effects-may-occur-with-cefuroxime-furotil', NULL, '2025-01-06 13:47:25', '2025-01-06 13:47:25'),
(300, '67', 'What precautions should be taken while using Cefuroxime (Furotil)?', 'Cefuroxime should be used cautiously in patients receiving potent diuretics and those with a history of colitis. While cephalosporins can generally be administered to penicillin-sensitive patients, there is some risk of cross-reactivity. Furotil should also be used carefully in patients with impaired renal function.', 'what-precautions-should-be-taken-while-using-cefuroxime-furotil', NULL, '2025-01-06 13:47:48', '2025-01-06 13:47:48'),
(301, '67', 'What are the therapeutic uses of Cefuroxime (Furotil)?', 'Furotil belongs to the second-generation cephalosporin class of antibiotics, widely used for treating bacterial infections resistant to other antibiotics.', 'what-are-the-therapeutic-uses-of-cefuroxime-furotil', NULL, '2025-01-06 13:48:12', '2025-01-06 13:48:12'),
(302, '67', 'How should Cefuroxime (Furotil) be stored?', 'Cefuroxime should be stored in a cool, dry place below 30C, protected from light and moisture. It should be kept out of the reach of children.', 'how-should-cefuroxime-furotil-be-stored', NULL, '2025-01-06 13:48:36', '2025-01-06 13:48:36'),
(303, '68', 'What is the pharmacology of Cefuroxime Axetil and Clavulanic Acid?', 'Cefuroxime Axetil is a second-generation cephalosporin antibiotic that works by inhibiting bacterial cell wall synthesis, thus killing the bacteria.\r\nClavulanic Acid is a beta-lactamase inhibitor that protects Cefuroxime from bacterial resistance mechanisms by inactivating beta-lactamase enzymes.', 'what-is-the-pharmacology-of-cefuroxime-axetil-and-clavulanic-acid', NULL, '2025-01-06 14:09:27', '2025-01-06 14:09:27'),
(304, '68', 'What is the recommended dosage for Cefuroxime Axetil with Clavulanic Acid?', 'Adults & Pediatric Patients (13 years and older):\r\nPharyngitis/Tonsillitis (mild to moderate): 250 mg every 12 hours for 10 days.\r\nAcute Sinusitis (mild to moderate): 250 mg every 12 hours for 10 days.\r\nChronic Bronchitis Exacerbation (mild to moderate): 250-500 mg every 12 hours for 10 days.\r\nUncomplicated Skin Infections: 250-500 mg every 12 hours for 10 days.\r\nUrinary Tract Infections: 250 mg every 12 hours for 7 to 10 days.\r\nGonorrhea: 1,000 mg as a single dose.\r\nEarly Lyme Disease: 500 mg every 12 hours for 20 days.\r\nPediatric Patients (3 months to 12 years) - Oral Suspension:\r\nPharyngitis/Tonsillitis: 20 mg/kg every 12 hours for 10 days.\r\nAcute Otitis Media/Sinusitis/Impetigo: 30 mg/kg every 12 hours for 10 days (Maximum dose 1,000 mg).', 'what-is-the-recommended-dosage-for-cefuroxime-axetil-with-clavulanic-acid', NULL, '2025-01-06 14:09:53', '2025-01-06 14:09:53'),
(305, '68', 'How should Cefuroxime Axetil with Clavulanic Acid be taken?', 'Tablets: Can be taken with or without food.\r\nSuspension: It is recommended to be taken with food for better absorption.', 'how-should-cefuroxime-axetil-with-clavulanic-acid-be-taken', NULL, '2025-01-06 14:10:24', '2025-01-06 14:10:24'),
(306, '68', 'What are the contraindications of Cefuroxime Axetil with Clavulanic Acid?', 'Cefuroxime Axetil with Clavulanic Acid is contraindicated in individuals with a known hypersensitivity to other beta-lactam antibiotics (e.g., penicillins, cephalosporins).', 'what-are-the-contraindications-of-cefuroxime-axetil-with-clavulanic-acid', NULL, '2025-01-06 14:10:40', '2025-01-06 14:10:40'),
(307, '68', 'What are the warnings and precautions for Cefuroxime Axetil with Clavulanic Acid?', 'Hypersensitivity Reactions: Discontinue the medication immediately if severe allergic reactions occur.\r\nClostridium difficile-associated Diarrhea (CDAD): Monitor for signs of diarrhea and evaluate for CDAD if necessary.', 'what-are-the-warnings-and-precautions-for-cefuroxime-axetil-with-clavulanic-acid', NULL, '2025-01-06 14:11:11', '2025-01-06 14:11:11'),
(308, '68', 'What are the common side effects of Cefuroxime Axetil with Clavulanic Acid?', 'Common: Diarrhea, nausea/vomiting, taste disturbances.\r\nRare: Headache, dizziness, and transient increases in liver enzymes.', 'what-are-the-common-side-effects-of-cefuroxime-axetil-with-clavulanic-acid', NULL, '2025-01-06 14:11:50', '2025-01-06 14:11:50'),
(309, '68', 'What is the use of Cefuroxime Axetil during pregnancy and lactation?', 'Pregnancy: Use cautiously, especially during the first trimester.\r\nLactation: Cefuroxime is excreted in breast milk, so it may be necessary to discontinue breastfeeding during treatment.', 'what-is-the-use-of-cefuroxime-axetil-during-pregnancy-and-lactation', NULL, '2025-01-06 14:12:16', '2025-01-06 14:12:16'),
(310, '68', 'What drug interactions should be considered with Cefuroxime Axetil with Clavulanic Acid?', 'Oral Contraceptives: Cefuroxime may reduce the effectiveness of oral contraceptives.\r\nProbenecid: Increases systemic exposure to the medication, avoid co-administration.\r\nGastric Acid Reducing Agents: May decrease the bioavailability of the drug.', 'what-drug-interactions-should-be-considered-with-cefuroxime-axetil-with-clavulanic-acid', NULL, '2025-01-06 14:12:51', '2025-01-06 14:12:51'),
(311, '68', 'How is Cefuroxime Axetil adjusted for renal impairment?', 'For patients with severe renal impairment (creatinine clearance <30 mL/min), dosage adjustments are recommended to avoid accumulation.', 'how-is-cefuroxime-axetil-adjusted-for-renal-impairment', NULL, '2025-01-06 14:13:14', '2025-01-06 14:13:14'),
(312, '68', 'What are the signs of overdose with Cefuroxime Axetil with Clavulanic Acid?', 'Overdose may cause convulsions or encephalopathy.\r\nDialysis can reduce cefuroxime levels in the body.', 'what-are-the-signs-of-overdose-with-cefuroxime-axetil-with-clavulanic-acid', NULL, '2025-01-06 14:13:35', '2025-01-06 14:13:35'),
(313, '68', 'How should Cefuroxime Axetil with Clavulanic Acid be stored?', 'Tablets: Store in a dry place at temperatures not exceeding 25C. Protect from light and moisture.\r\nSuspension: After reconstitution, store in a refrigerator (2-8C) and use within 7 days. Unreconstituted powder should be stored in a dry place at temperatures not exceeding 25C.', 'how-should-cefuroxime-axetil-with-clavulanic-acid-be-stored', NULL, '2025-01-06 14:13:55', '2025-01-06 14:13:55'),
(314, '69', 'What is the composition of Gemicin?', 'Each Gemicin tablet contains Gemifloxacin Mesylate INN, equivalent to 320 mg of Gemifloxacin.', 'what-is-the-composition-of-gemicin', NULL, '2025-01-06 14:30:24', '2025-01-06 14:30:24'),
(315, '69', 'What is Gemicin used for?', 'Gemicin is indicated for the treatment of infections caused by susceptible strains of microorganisms in the following conditions:\r\n\r\nAcute bacterial exacerbation of chronic bronchitis caused by Streptococcus pneumoniae, Haemophilus influenzae, Haemophilus parainfluenzae, or Moraxella catarrhalis.\r\nCommunity-acquired pneumonia (mild to moderate severity) caused by:\r\nStreptococcus pneumoniae (including multi-drug resistant strains - MDRSP),\r\nHaemophilus influenzae, Moraxella catarrhalis, Mycoplasma pneumoniae, Chlamydia pneumoniae, or Klebsiella pneumoniae.', 'what-is-gemicin-used-for', NULL, '2025-01-06 14:30:47', '2025-01-06 14:30:47'),
(316, '69', 'What is the recommended dosage for Gemicin?', 'Acute bacterial exacerbation of chronic bronchitis: One 320 mg tablet daily for 5 days.\r\nCommunity-acquired pneumonia (mild to moderate severity):\r\nDue to S. pneumoniae, H. influenzae, M. pneumoniae, or C. pneumoniae: One 320 mg tablet daily for 5 days.\r\nDue to multi-drug resistant S. pneumoniae, K. pneumoniae, or M. catarrhalis: One 320 mg tablet daily for 7 days.\r\nThe recommended dose and duration should not be exceeded.', 'what-is-the-recommended-dosage-for-gemicin', NULL, '2025-01-06 14:31:08', '2025-01-06 14:31:08'),
(317, '69', 'Is there a dosage adjustment required for renally impaired patients?', 'No dose adjustment is required for patients with creatinine clearance >40 mL/min.\r\nFor patients with creatinine clearance 40 mL/min: 160 mg every 24 hours.\r\nPatients on routine hemodialysis or CAPD: 160 mg every 24 hours.', 'is-there-a-dosage-adjustment-required-for-renally-impaired-patients', NULL, '2025-01-06 14:31:33', '2025-01-06 14:31:33'),
(318, '69', 'Is there a dosage adjustment required for hepatically impaired patients?', 'No dosage adjustment is recommended for patients with mild, moderate, or severe hepatic impairment.', 'is-there-a-dosage-adjustment-required-for-hepatically-impaired-patients', NULL, '2025-01-06 14:31:57', '2025-01-06 14:31:57'),
(319, '69', 'What are the contraindications of Gemicin?', 'Gemicin is contraindicated in patients with a history of:\r\nHypersensitivity to Gemifloxacin, fluoroquinolone antibiotics, or any product components.', 'what-are-the-contraindications-of-gemicin', NULL, '2025-01-06 14:32:21', '2025-01-06 14:32:21'),
(320, '69', 'What are the common adverse effects of Gemicin?', 'Gastrointestinal: Nausea, upper GI discomfort.\r\nCNS: Headache, insomnia, dizziness. Rare: Hallucinations, depression, psychotic reactions.\r\nRenal: Interstitial nephritis.\r\nCardiovascular: QTc prolongation, torsades de pointes, arrhythmias.\r\nSkin: Rash.', 'what-are-the-common-adverse-effects-of-gemicin', NULL, '2025-01-06 14:32:41', '2025-01-06 14:32:41');
INSERT INTO `overviews` (`id`, `P_id`, `question`, `answare`, `slug`, `sequece`, `created_at`, `updated_at`) VALUES
(321, '69', 'What precautions should be taken while using Gemicin?', 'QT Interval Prolongation: Avoid concurrent use with other drugs that prolong the QT interval and in patients with risk factors (e.g., hypokalemia, bradycardia).\r\nRenal Insufficiency: Monitor renal function.\r\nGlucose-6-Phosphate Dehydrogenase Deficiency: Use cautiously.\r\nSunlight Exposure: Avoid excessive exposure to sunlight.\r\nDiabetes Mellitus: Monitor for disturbances in blood glucose levels, particularly in diabetic patients on oral hypoglycemic agents or insulin.', 'what-precautions-should-be-taken-while-using-gemicin', NULL, '2025-01-06 14:33:00', '2025-01-06 14:33:00'),
(322, '69', 'What are the drug interactions of Gemicin?', 'Divalent cations (e.g., aluminum, magnesium, zinc, iron, calcium, antacids, sucralfate): These can reduce the bioavailability of Gemifloxacin, leading to therapeutic failure.', 'what-are-the-drug-interactions-of-gemicin', NULL, '2025-01-06 14:33:23', '2025-01-06 14:33:23'),
(323, '69', 'Can Gemicin be used during pregnancy?', 'Gemicin is classified as Pregnancy Category C, indicating that the risk is unknown due to inadequate human studies. It should only be used if the potential benefit outweighs the risk.', 'can-gemicin-be-used-during-pregnancy', NULL, '2025-01-06 14:33:46', '2025-01-06 14:33:46'),
(324, '69', 'How should Gemicin be stored?', 'Gemicin should be stored in a cool, dry place, away from light and moisture.', 'how-should-gemicin-be-stored', NULL, '2025-01-06 14:34:04', '2025-01-06 14:34:04'),
(325, '70', 'What is the composition of Fosfogen?', 'Each sachet of Fosfogen contains Fosfomycin Trometamol BP, equivalent to Fosfomycin 3 gm.', 'what-is-the-composition-of-fosfogen', NULL, '2025-01-06 15:20:43', '2025-01-06 15:20:43'),
(326, '70', 'What type of antibiotic is Fosfomycin?', 'Fosfomycin is a synthetic, broad-spectrum, bactericidal antibiotic for oral administration.', 'what-type-of-antibiotic-is-fosfomycin', NULL, '2025-01-06 15:21:05', '2025-01-06 15:21:05'),
(327, '70', 'What are the indications for using Fosfogen?', 'Fosfogen is indicated only for the treatment of uncomplicated urinary tract infections (acute cystitis) in women caused by susceptible strains of Escherichia coli and Enterococcus faecalis.', 'what-are-the-indications-for-using-fosfogen', NULL, '2025-01-06 15:21:28', '2025-01-06 15:21:28'),
(328, '70', 'What is the recommended dosage and administration for Fosfogen?', 'Dosage: Women aged 18 years and older should take 1 sachet of Fosfogen.\r\nAdministration:\r\nDissolve the contents of the sachet in half a glass of water (do not use hot water).\r\nStir to dissolve completely.\r\nTake the solution immediately after preparation.\r\nFosfogen can be taken with or without food.', 'what-is-the-recommended-dosage-and-administration-for-fosfogen', NULL, '2025-01-06 15:21:52', '2025-01-06 15:21:52'),
(329, '70', 'What are the common adverse effects of Fosfogen?', 'Common adverse effects:\r\nDiarrhea\r\nNausea\r\nVomiting\r\nSkin rash', 'what-are-the-common-adverse-effects-of-fosfogen', NULL, '2025-01-06 15:22:23', '2025-01-06 15:22:23'),
(330, '70', 'What precautions should be observed while taking Fosfogen?', 'Do not take more than one single dose to treat a single episode of acute cystitis.\r\nIf symptoms persist after 23 days, contact a healthcare provider.\r\nPatients should report watery or bloody stools, with or without stomach cramps and fever, even if it occurs months after the last dose.', 'what-precautions-should-be-observed-while-taking-fosfogen', NULL, '2025-01-06 15:22:45', '2025-01-06 15:22:45'),
(331, '70', 'What are the contraindications of Fosfogen?', 'Fosfogen is contraindicated in patients with known hypersensitivity to Fosfomycin or any of its components.', 'what-are-the-contraindications-of-fosfogen', NULL, '2025-01-06 15:23:07', '2025-01-06 15:23:07'),
(332, '70', 'Can Fosfogen be used during pregnancy?', 'Fosfomycin is classified as Pregnancy Category B:\r\nAnimal studies do not indicate harm to the fetus, but adequate human studies are lacking.\r\nFosfogen should be used during pregnancy only if clearly needed.', 'can-fosfogen-be-used-during-pregnancy', NULL, '2025-01-06 15:23:37', '2025-01-06 15:23:37'),
(333, '70', 'Is Fosfogen safe for use during lactation?', 'It is not known whether Fosfomycin Trometamol is excreted in human milk. Caution is advised when administering to breastfeeding mothers.', 'is-fosfogen-safe-for-use-during-lactation', NULL, '2025-01-06 15:24:02', '2025-01-06 15:24:02'),
(334, '70', 'Is Fosfogen recommended for pediatric use?', 'The safety and effectiveness of Fosfogen in children aged 12 years and under have not been established.', 'is-fosfogen-recommended-for-pediatric-use', NULL, '2025-01-06 15:24:24', '2025-01-06 15:24:24'),
(335, '70', 'Are there any significant drug interactions with Fosfogen?', 'Metoclopramide: Co-administration reduces the serum concentration and urinary excretion of Fosfomycin.\r\nOther drugs that increase gastrointestinal motility may have similar effects.', 'are-there-any-significant-drug-interactions-with-fosfogen', NULL, '2025-01-06 15:24:45', '2025-01-06 15:24:45'),
(336, '70', 'What are the symptoms of Fosfogen overdose?', 'Overdose symptoms may include:\r\nVestibular loss\r\nImpaired hearing\r\nMetallic taste\r\nGeneral decline in taste perception\r\nManagement: Treatment should be symptomatic and supportive.', 'what-are-the-symptoms-of-fosfogen-overdose', NULL, '2025-01-06 15:25:12', '2025-01-06 15:25:12'),
(337, '70', 'How should Fosfogen be stored?', 'Store at a temperature not exceeding 30C in a dry place.\r\nProtect from light and moisture.', 'how-should-fosfogen-be-stored', NULL, '2025-01-06 15:25:35', '2025-01-06 15:25:35'),
(338, '71', 'What are the indications for Rifaximin?', 'Rifaximin is indicated for the treatment of:\r\nAcute Infectious Diarrhea, including Travelers\' Diarrhea Diarrhea-predominant Irritable Bowel Syndrome (IBS-D) Hepatic Encephalopathy (HE)', 'what-are-the-indications-for-rifaximin', NULL, '2025-01-06 16:08:13', '2025-01-06 16:08:13'),
(339, '71', 'What is the mechanism of action of Rifaximin?', 'Rifaximin binds to the beta-subunit of bacterial DNA-dependent RNA polymerase, inhibiting bacterial RNA synthesis. Due to limited absorption, its effects are primarily localized to the gastrointestinal tract.', 'what-is-the-mechanism-of-action-of-rifaximin', NULL, '2025-01-06 16:08:36', '2025-01-06 16:08:36'),
(340, '71', 'How should Rifaximin be administered?', 'Rifaximin tablets can be taken orally with or without food. Always follow the prescribed dosage regimen as directed by a healthcare provider.', 'how-should-rifaximin-be-administered', NULL, '2025-01-06 16:08:56', '2025-01-06 16:08:56'),
(341, '71', 'What precautions should be considered when using Rifaximin?', 'Renal Insufficiency: Pharmacokinetics in patients with impaired renal function have not been studied.\r\nHepatic Insufficiency: No dosage adjustment is needed, but caution is advised in severe hepatic impairment.', 'what-precautions-should-be-considered-when-using-rifaximin', NULL, '2025-01-06 16:28:21', '2025-01-06 16:28:21'),
(342, '71', 'What are the common side effects of Rifaximin?', 'Most individuals tolerate Rifaximin well, but some may experience:\r\nDizziness\r\nGas\r\nHeadache\r\nNausea\r\nTiredness\r\nWhat are the common side effects of Rifaximin?\r\nAnswer:\r\nMost individuals tolerate Rifaximin well, but some may experience:\r\n\r\nDizziness\r\nGas\r\nHeadache\r\nNausea\r\nTiredness', 'what-are-the-common-side-effects-of-rifaximin', NULL, '2025-01-06 16:28:49', '2025-01-06 16:28:49'),
(343, '71', 'Can Rifaximin be used during pregnancy or lactation?', 'Pregnancy:\r\nCategory C: Use only if potential benefits outweigh potential risks to the fetus.\r\nLactation:\r\nIt is unclear whether Rifaximin is excreted in human milk. A decision should be made to discontinue either the drug or nursing.', 'can-rifaximin-be-used-during-pregnancy-or-lactation', NULL, '2025-01-06 16:29:13', '2025-01-06 16:29:13'),
(344, '71', 'Is Rifaximin safe for children and adolescents?', 'Children:\r\nThe safety and effectiveness of Rifaximin 200 mg for travelers\' diarrhea in pediatric patients under 12 years have not been established.\r\nThe safety and effectiveness of Rifaximin 550 mg for hepatic encephalopathy and IBS-D in patients under 18 years are not established.\r\nAdolescents:\r\nInsufficient data exist to determine differences in responses between older individuals (65+) and younger patients.', 'is-rifaximin-safe-for-children-and-adolescents', NULL, '2025-01-06 16:29:43', '2025-01-06 16:29:43'),
(345, '71', 'Are there any significant drug interactions with Rifaximin?', 'In vitro studies: Potential interaction with cytochrome P450 (CYP3A4).\r\nClinical studies:\r\nRifaximin does not significantly affect the pharmacokinetics of Midazolam or oral contraceptives containing ethinyl estradiol and norgestimate.\r\nNo significant interactions with human cytochrome P450 isozymes are expected.', 'are-there-any-significant-drug-interactions-with-rifaximin', NULL, '2025-01-06 16:30:17', '2025-01-06 16:30:17'),
(346, '71', 'What should be done in case of Rifaximin overdose?', 'Symptoms: Adverse reactions are similar to those seen with placebo, even at higher-than-recommended doses.\r\nManagement: Discontinue Rifaximin, provide symptomatic treatment, and offer supportive care as needed.', 'what-should-be-done-in-case-of-rifaximin-overdose', NULL, '2025-01-06 16:30:54', '2025-01-06 16:30:54'),
(347, '71', 'How should Rifaximin be stored?', 'Store below 30C in a dry place.\r\nProtect from light.', 'how-should-rifaximin-be-stored', NULL, '2025-01-06 16:31:18', '2025-01-06 16:31:18'),
(352, '72', 'What is Neopenem?', 'Neopenem is a carbapenem antibiotic used to treat a wide range of bacterial infections. It works by inhibiting bacterial cell wall synthesis, leading to the death of the bacteria.', 'what-is-neopenem', NULL, '2025-01-06 17:39:47', '2025-01-06 17:39:47'),
(353, '72', 'What is the composition of Neopenem?', 'Each vial of Neopenem contains Meropenem (as the trihydrate), equivalent to the labeled dose for intravenous administration.', 'what-is-the-composition-of-neopenem', NULL, '2025-01-06 17:40:05', '2025-01-06 17:40:05'),
(354, '72', 'What are the indications for using Neopenem?', 'Neopenem is indicated for the treatment of:\r\nLower respiratory tract infections\r\nUrinary tract infections (including complicated infections)\r\nIntra-abdominal infections\r\nGynecological infections (e.g., postpartum infections)\r\nSkin and skin structure infections\r\nMeningitis\r\nSepticaemia\r\nEmpiric treatment of bacterial infections in neutropenic patients', 'what-are-the-indications-for-using-neopenem', NULL, '2025-01-06 17:40:34', '2025-01-06 17:40:34'),
(355, '72', 'What is the usual dosage of Neopenem for adults?', 'The usual adult dose is 500 mg to 1 g IV every 8 hours, depending on the type and severity of the infection.\r\n\r\nFebrile Neutropenic Episodes: 1 g IV every 8 hours\r\nMeningitis: 2 g IV every 8 hours', 'what-is-the-usual-dosage-of-neopenem-for-adults', NULL, '2025-01-06 17:40:53', '2025-01-06 17:40:53'),
(356, '72', 'Are dosage adjustments required for elderly patients?', 'No dosage adjustments are required for elderly patients if renal function is normal (creatinine clearance >50 mL/min).', 'are-dosage-adjustments-required-for-elderly-patients', NULL, '2025-01-06 17:41:13', '2025-01-06 17:41:13'),
(357, '72', 'What is the recommended dose for children?', 'For children over 3 months:\r\n10-40 mg/kg IV every 8 hours, depending on infection type and severity.\r\n\r\nSpecial cases:\r\nFebrile Neutropenic Episodes: 20 mg/kg every 8 hours\r\nMeningitis: 40 mg/kg every 8 hours', 'what-is-the-recommended-dose-for-children', NULL, '2025-01-06 17:41:42', '2025-01-06 17:41:42'),
(358, '72', 'Is Neopenem safe for patients with renal impairment?', 'Yes, but dosage adjustments are needed based on creatinine clearance:\r\n\r\nCreatinine Clearance (mL/min)	Dose	Frequency\r\n26-50	Full dose	Every 12 hours\r\n10-25	Half dose	Every 12 hours\r\n<10	Half dose	Every 24 hours\r\nFor hemodialysis patients, administer the recommended dose post-dialysis.', 'is-neopenem-safe-for-patients-with-renal-impairment', NULL, '2025-01-06 17:42:13', '2025-01-06 17:42:13'),
(359, '72', 'Can Neopenem be used during pregnancy?', 'Neopenem is classified as Pregnancy Category B. It should only be used if the potential benefits outweigh the risks to the fetus.', 'can-neopenem-be-used-during-pregnancy', NULL, '2025-01-06 17:42:34', '2025-01-06 17:42:34'),
(360, '72', 'What are the common side effects of Neopenem?', 'Common side effects include:\r\nNausea\r\nVomiting\r\nDiarrhea\r\nRash\r\nHeadache\r\nInjection site inflammation\r\nRare but serious side effects include:\r\n\r\nPseudomembranous colitis\r\nAnaphylaxis\r\nStevens-Johnson syndrome\r\nConvulsions', 'what-are-the-common-side-effects-of-neopenem', NULL, '2025-01-06 17:43:00', '2025-01-06 17:43:00'),
(361, '72', 'Are there any drug interactions with Neopenem?', 'Yes, notable interactions include:\r\nProbenecid: Increases plasma levels and half-life of meropenem. Avoid co-administration.\r\nValproic Acid: May reduce serum levels, potentially leading to subtherapeutic effects.', 'are-there-any-drug-interactions-with-neopenem', NULL, '2025-01-06 17:43:30', '2025-01-06 17:43:30'),
(362, '72', 'How should Neopenem be stored?', 'Store Neopenem below 25C in a dry place. Reconstituted solutions should be used within 2 hours if kept at room temperature or within 12 hours if refrigerated (2-8C). Do not freeze.', 'how-should-neopenem-be-stored', NULL, '2025-01-06 17:43:50', '2025-01-06 17:43:50'),
(363, '73', 'What is Nitrofurantoin (NFT) used for?', 'NFT is specifically indicated for the treatment and prophylaxis of urinary tract infections (UTIs) caused by susceptible strains of bacteria such as:\r\nEscherichia coli\r\nEnterococci\r\nStaphylococcus aureus\r\nStaphylococcus saprophyticus\r\nCertain susceptible strains of Klebsiella and Enterobacter species.', 'what-is-nitrofurantoin-nft-used-for', NULL, '2025-01-06 17:57:48', '2025-01-06 17:57:48'),
(364, '73', 'What are the available formulations of NFT?', 'NFT is available in the following forms:\r\n50 mg Capsule: Each capsule contains Nitrofurantoin (macrocrystal) 50 mg.\r\n100 mg Capsule: Each capsule contains Nitrofurantoin (macrocrystal) 100 mg.\r\nOral Suspension: Each 5 ml suspension contains Nitrofurantoin Monohydrate 25 mg.', 'what-are-the-available-formulations-of-nft', NULL, '2025-01-06 17:58:13', '2025-01-06 17:58:13'),
(365, '73', 'How does Nitrofurantoin work?', 'Nitrofurantoin works by:\r\nInactivating or altering bacterial ribosomal proteins and other macromolecules, leading to bacterial death.\r\nIt is highly soluble in urine, where it exerts its antibacterial activity.', 'how-does-nitrofurantoin-work', NULL, '2025-01-06 17:58:44', '2025-01-06 17:58:44'),
(366, '73', 'How should Nitrofurantoin be administered for adults?', 'Uncomplicated UTIs: 50-100 mg four times daily for 7 days.\r\nLong-term suppressive therapy: 50-100 mg once daily at bedtime.\r\nProphylaxis: 50 mg four times daily during the procedure and for 3 days thereafter.', 'how-should-nitrofurantoin-be-administered-for-adults', NULL, '2025-01-06 17:59:10', '2025-01-06 17:59:10'),
(367, '73', 'What is the recommended dosage for children?', 'Children: 5-7 mg/kg/day in four divided doses.\r\nPediatric dosing for oral suspension:\r\n7-11 kg:  (2.5 ml) teaspoonful 4 times daily.\r\n12-21 kg: 1 (5 ml) teaspoonful 4 times daily.\r\n22-30 kg: 1 (7.5 ml) teaspoonful 4 times daily.\r\n31-41 kg: 2 (10 ml) teaspoonfuls 4 times daily.\r\nTherapy should continue for one week or at least 3 days after urine sterility is achieved.', 'what-is-the-recommended-dosage-for-children', NULL, '2025-01-06 17:59:37', '2025-01-06 17:59:37'),
(368, '73', 'What are the potential drug interactions with Nitrofurantoin?', 'Antacids containing magnesium trisilicate: Reduce the absorption of NFT.\r\nUricosuric drugs (e.g., Probenecid, Sulfinpyrazone): Inhibit renal tubular secretion of NFT, reducing its efficacy.', 'what-are-the-potential-drug-interactions-with-nitrofurantoin', NULL, '2025-01-06 18:00:05', '2025-01-06 18:00:05'),
(369, '73', 'Are there any contraindications for using NFT?', 'Yes, NFT is contraindicated in:\r\nPatients with significant renal impairment (anuria, oliguria).\r\nPregnant patients at 38-42 weeks of gestation, during labor, or delivery.\r\nPatients with hypersensitivity to Nitrofurantoin.', 'are-there-any-contraindications-for-using-nft', NULL, '2025-01-06 18:00:39', '2025-01-06 18:00:39'),
(370, '73', 'What are the common side effects of NFT?', 'Common side effects include:\r\nNausea\r\nHeadache\r\nFlatulence\r\nLess frequent: Diarrhea, abdominal pain, dizziness, and drowsiness.', 'what-are-the-common-side-effects-of-nft', NULL, '2025-01-06 18:01:05', '2025-01-06 18:01:05'),
(371, '73', 'Can Nitrofurantoin be used during pregnancy and lactation?', 'Pregnancy: NFT is classified as Pregnancy Category B. Use only if clearly needed. Avoid use during late pregnancy (38-42 weeks).\r\nLactation: NFT passes into breast milk in trace amounts. Avoid use in nursing infants under one month.', 'can-nitrofurantoin-be-used-during-pregnancy-and-lactation', NULL, '2025-01-06 18:01:27', '2025-01-06 18:01:27'),
(372, '73', 'What precautions should be taken while using NFT?', 'Discontinue use if pulmonary reactions (acute, sub-acute, or chronic) occur.\r\nAvoid taking antacid preparations containing magnesium trisilicate with NFT.', 'what-precautions-should-be-taken-while-using-nft', NULL, '2025-01-06 18:02:24', '2025-01-06 18:02:24'),
(373, '73', 'What happens in case of an overdose of NFT?', 'Symptoms: Vomiting is the most common symptom.\r\nManagement: Induction of emesis is recommended, followed by symptomatic treatment.', 'what-happens-in-case-of-an-overdose-of-nft', NULL, '2025-01-06 18:02:49', '2025-01-06 18:02:49'),
(374, '73', 'How should NFT be stored?', 'Store NFT below 30C in a dry place, away from light, and out of reach of children.', 'how-should-nft-be-stored', NULL, '2025-01-06 18:03:12', '2025-01-06 18:03:12'),
(375, '74', 'What are the available compositions of Ceftriaxone?', 'Ceftriaxone is available in the following forms:\r\n250 mg i.v./i.m. Injection: Contains Ceftriaxone Sodium USP 298.23 mg, equivalent to Ceftriaxone 250 mg.\r\n500 mg i.v./i.m. Injection: Contains Ceftriaxone Sodium USP 596.46 mg, equivalent to Ceftriaxone 500 mg.\r\n1 g i.v./i.m. Injection: Contains Ceftriaxone Sodium USP 1.193 g, equivalent to Ceftriaxone 1 g.\r\n2 g i.v. Infusion: Contains Ceftriaxone Sodium USP 2.386 g, equivalent to Ceftriaxone 2 g.', 'what-are-the-available-compositions-of-ceftriaxone', NULL, '2025-01-07 09:07:42', '2025-01-07 09:07:42'),
(376, '74', 'What solvents are used for Ceftriaxone preparation?', 'For i.m. injection: 1% lidocaine hydrochloride solution.\r\nFor i.v. injection: Sterile water for injection.', 'what-solvents-are-used-for-ceftriaxone-preparation', NULL, '2025-01-07 09:08:07', '2025-01-07 09:08:07'),
(377, '74', 'How does Ceftriaxone work?', 'Ceftriaxone is a bactericidal antibiotic that inhibits bacterial cell wall synthesis. It is highly stable against most -lactamases, including penicillinases and cephalosporinases, which enhances its effectiveness against a wide range of microorganisms.', 'how-does-ceftriaxone-work', NULL, '2025-01-07 09:08:36', '2025-01-07 09:08:36'),
(378, '74', 'Which microorganisms are susceptible to Ceftriaxone?', 'Gram-positive Aerobes:\r\n\r\nStaphylococcus aureus (including penicillinase-producing strains)\r\nStaphylococcus epidermidis\r\nStreptococcus pneumoniae, Str. pyogenes, Str. agalactiae, etc.\r\nGram-negative Aerobes:\r\n\r\nEscherichia coli, Klebsiella spp., Neisseria gonorrhoeae, Haemophilus influenzae, etc.\r\nAnaerobic Organisms:\r\n\r\nBacteroides spp., Clostridium spp. (except Cl. difficile), Peptostreptococcus spp., etc.', 'which-microorganisms-are-susceptible-to-ceftriaxone', NULL, '2025-01-07 09:09:01', '2025-01-07 09:09:01'),
(379, '74', 'What are the pharmacokinetics of Ceftriaxone?', 'Absorption: 100% bioavailability with intramuscular administration. Peak plasma concentration (~81 mg/L) is reached in 23 hours after a 1 g dose.\r\nDistribution: Widely distributed in body fluids, including cerebrospinal fluid and pleural fluid.\r\nElimination: 5060% excreted in urine, 4050% via bile. Half-life is ~8 hours in adults.', 'what-are-the-pharmacokinetics-of-ceftriaxone', NULL, '2025-01-07 09:09:25', '2025-01-07 09:09:25'),
(380, '74', 'What are the indications for Ceftriaxone?', 'Ceftriaxone is indicated for treating infections caused by susceptible microorganisms, such as:\r\nSepsis\r\nMeningitis\r\nAbdominal infections\r\nRespiratory tract infections\r\nBone and joint infections\r\nUrinary tract infections\r\nGonorrhea', 'what-are-the-indications-for-ceftriaxone', NULL, '2025-01-07 09:09:55', '2025-01-07 09:09:55'),
(381, '74', 'What are the dosage guidelines for Ceftriaxone?', 'Adults and Children (12 years): 12 g once daily; severe cases may require up to 4 g/day.\r\nNeonates/Infants: 2050 mg/kg daily for neonates; 2080 mg/kg for older children.\r\nMeningitis: 100 mg/kg once daily (maximum 4 g/day).', 'what-are-the-dosage-guidelines-for-ceftriaxone', NULL, '2025-01-07 09:10:23', '2025-01-07 09:10:23'),
(382, '74', 'How is Ceftriaxone administered?', 'i.m. Injection: Dissolve 250 mg or 500 mg in 2 mL, and 1 g in 3.5 mL, of 1% lidocaine solution.\r\ni.v. Injection: Dissolve 250 mg or 500 mg in 5 mL, and 1 g in 10 mL, of sterile water. Administer over 24 minutes.', 'how-is-ceftriaxone-administered', NULL, '2025-01-07 09:11:00', '2025-01-07 09:11:00'),
(383, '74', 'What precautions should be taken while using Ceftriaxone?', 'Monitor for anaphylactic reactions.\r\nUse with caution in hyperbilirubinemic neonates.\r\nPerform regular blood count monitoring during prolonged therapy.', 'what-precautions-should-be-taken-while-using-ceftriaxone', NULL, '2025-01-07 09:11:31', '2025-01-07 09:11:31'),
(384, '74', 'What are the contraindications for Ceftriaxone?', 'Ceftriaxone is contraindicated in patients with:\r\nKnown hypersensitivity to cephalosporins.', 'what-are-the-contraindications-for-ceftriaxone', NULL, '2025-01-07 09:11:56', '2025-01-07 09:11:56'),
(385, '75', 'What are the indications for using Rocef (Cefradine)?', 'Rocef is used to treat infections caused by sensitive organisms, including:\r\nUpper respiratory tract infections: Pharyngitis, sinusitis, otitis media, tonsillitis, laryngotracheobronchitis.\r\nLower respiratory tract infections: Acute and chronic bronchitis, lobar and bronchopneumonia.\r\nUrinary tract infections: Cystitis, urethritis, pyelonephritis.\r\nSkin and soft tissue infections: Abscess, cellulitis, furunculosis, impetigo.\r\nGastrointestinal tract infections: Bacillary dysentery, enteritis, peritonitis.\r\nBone and joint infections.\r\nSurgical prophylaxis: Perioperative prophylactic administration to reduce post-operative infections.', 'what-are-the-indications-for-using-rocef-cefradine', NULL, '2025-01-07 12:33:45', '2025-01-07 12:33:45'),
(386, '75', 'What is the recommended dosage for Rocef?', 'For Adults (Oral):\r\n\r\nUsual dose: 12 g daily in 24 divided doses.\r\nSevere infections: Up to 4 g daily in divided doses.\r\nSpecific infections:\r\n\r\nSkin and respiratory tract infections: 250 mg every 6 hours or 500 mg every 12 hours.\r\nLobar pneumonia: 500 mg every 6 hours or 1 g every 12 hours.\r\nUrinary tract infections: 500 mg every 12 hours.\r\nGastrointestinal tract infections: 500 mg 34 times daily.\r\nFor Children (Oral):\r\n\r\nTotal dose: 2550 mg/kg/day in 24 divided doses.\r\nPerioperative Prophylaxis:\r\n\r\n12 g intramuscularly or intravenously, followed by appropriate oral or parenteral doses.', 'what-is-the-recommended-dosage-for-rocef', NULL, '2025-01-07 12:34:30', '2025-01-07 12:34:30'),
(387, '75', 'How is the dosage adjusted in renal impairment?', 'Doses are adjusted based on creatinine clearance:\r\n\r\nCreatinine Clearance (ml/min)	Interval (hrs)\r\n> 20	612\r\n1519	1224\r\n1014	2440\r\n59	4050\r\n< 5	5070', 'how-is-the-dosage-adjusted-in-renal-impairment', NULL, '2025-01-07 12:34:54', '2025-01-07 12:34:54'),
(388, '75', 'What are the side effects of Rocef?', 'What are the side effects of Rocef?\r\nPossible side effects include:\r\nGastrointestinal: Nausea, vomiting, diarrhea, abdominal discomfort.\r\nAllergic reactions: Skin rashes, urticaria, eosinophilia, angioedema, anaphylaxis.\r\nOther reactions: Elevated liver enzymes, neutropenia, superinfection (e.g., Candida), pseudomembranous colitis, thrombophlebitis (IV use).', 'what-are-the-side-effects-of-rocef', NULL, '2025-01-07 12:35:14', '2025-01-07 12:35:14'),
(389, '75', 'What precautions should be taken when using Rocef?', 'Use cautiously in patients hypersensitive to penicillins.\r\nAvoid in patients with known cephalosporin hypersensitivity.\r\nMonitor liver function and blood counts during long-term use.', 'what-precautions-should-be-taken-when-using-rocef', NULL, '2025-01-07 12:35:34', '2025-01-07 12:35:34'),
(390, '75', 'Can Rocef be used during pregnancy and lactation?', 'Pregnancy: Use only if clearly indicated, as safety has not been firmly established.\r\nLactation: Use with caution, as Rocef is excreted in breast milk.', 'can-rocef-be-used-during-pregnancy-and-lactation', NULL, '2025-01-07 12:35:55', '2025-01-07 12:35:55'),
(391, '75', 'How should Rocef powder for suspension be reconstituted?', 'Shake the bottle well to loosen the powder.\r\nAdd 65 ml of cooled, boiled water using the provided cup.\r\nShake the bottle gently until the powder dissolves.\r\nShake well before each use.', 'how-should-rocef-powder-for-suspension-be-reconstituted', NULL, '2025-01-07 12:36:15', '2025-01-07 12:36:15'),
(392, '75', 'What storage conditions are required for Rocef?', 'Store capsules and dry powder in a cool, dry place, away from light.\r\nReconstituted syrup:\r\nStore at room temperature for up to 7 days.\r\nRefrigerate for up to 14 days.\r\nProtect from direct sunlight and keep out of reach of children.', 'what-storage-conditions-are-required-for-rocef', NULL, '2025-01-07 12:36:43', '2025-01-07 12:36:43'),
(393, '76', 'What type of antibiotic is Cefpodoxime Roxetil?', 'Cefpodoxime Roxetil is a third-generation, semi-synthetic cephalosporin antibiotic. It is an orally administered, extended-spectrum drug that is bactericidal, meaning it kills bacteria by inhibiting bacterial cell wall synthesis.', 'what-type-of-antibiotic-is-cefpodoxime-roxetil', NULL, '2025-01-07 13:03:23', '2025-01-07 13:03:23'),
(394, '76', 'What types of bacteria does Cefpodoxime Roxetil target?', 'Cefpodoxime Roxetil is effective against both gram-positive and gram-negative bacteria.\r\nGram-positive bacteria: Includes S. aureus (including penicillinase-producing strains), S. pneumoniae, S. pyogenes, and others.\r\nGram-negative bacteria: Includes E. coli, K. pneumoniae, H. influenzae, N. gonorrhoeae, and others.', 'what-types-of-bacteria-does-cefpodoxime-roxetil-target', NULL, '2025-01-07 13:03:53', '2025-01-07 13:03:53'),
(395, '76', 'What conditions is Cefpodoxime Roxetil used to treat?', 'Cefpodoxime Roxetil is indicated for treating the following conditions:\r\nLower respiratory tract infections: Acute community-acquired pneumonia, acute bacterial exacerbation of chronic bronchitis.\r\nUpper respiratory tract infections: Acute otitis media, acute maxillary sinusitis, pharyngitis, tonsillitis.\r\nSexually transmitted diseases: Uncomplicated gonorrhea (urethral, cervical, ano-rectal in women).\r\nUrinary tract infections: Cystitis, pyuria.\r\nSkin and soft tissue infections: Furuncle, cellulitis, subcutaneous abscess, infectious atheroma.', 'what-conditions-is-cefpodoxime-roxetil-used-to-treat', NULL, '2025-01-07 13:04:16', '2025-01-07 13:04:16'),
(396, '76', 'What is the typical dosage for adults (12 years and older)?', 'Acute community-acquired pneumonia: 200 mg every 12 hours for 14 days (Total daily dose: 400 mg).\r\nAcute bacterial exacerbation of chronic bronchitis: 200 mg every 12 hours for 10 days (Total daily dose: 400 mg).\r\nUncomplicated gonorrhea: 200 mg as a single dose.\r\nSkin & soft tissue infections: 400 mg every 12 hours for 7-14 days (Total daily dose: 800 mg).\r\nPharyngitis and tonsillitis: 100 mg every 12 hours for 5-10 days (Total daily dose: 200 mg).\r\nUrinary tract infections: 100 mg every 12 hours for 7 days (Total daily dose: 200 mg).', 'what-is-the-typical-dosage-for-adults-12-years-and-older', NULL, '2025-01-07 13:04:42', '2025-01-07 13:04:42'),
(397, '76', 'How is Cefpodoxime Roxetil dosed for children?', '15 days - 6 months: 4 mg/kg every 12 hours.\r\n6 months - 2 years: 40 mg every 12 hours.\r\n3 - 8 years: 80 mg every 12 hours.\r\nOver 9 years: 100 mg every 12 hours.', 'how-is-cefpodoxime-roxetil-dosed-for-children', NULL, '2025-01-07 13:05:04', '2025-01-07 13:05:04'),
(398, '76', 'Does Cefpodoxime Roxetil require dose adjustments in patients with renal dysfunction?', 'Yes, for severe renal impairment (creatinine clearance < 30 ml/min), the dosing interval should be extended to 24 hours.', 'does-cefpodoxime-roxetil-require-dose-adjustments-in-patients-with-renal-dysfunction', NULL, '2025-01-07 13:05:24', '2025-01-07 13:05:24'),
(399, '76', 'Are there any common side effects of Cefpodoxime Roxetil?', 'Gastrointestinal side effects: Diarrhea, nausea, abdominal pain, dyspepsia.\r\nOther side effects: Fungal infections (skin and vaginal), headache, chest pain, myalgia, dizziness, vertigo, cough.\r\nIn children: Higher incidence of fungal skin rashes compared to adults.', 'are-there-any-common-side-effects-of-cefpodoxime-roxetil', NULL, '2025-01-07 13:05:46', '2025-01-07 13:05:46'),
(400, '76', 'What precautions should be taken when using Cefpodoxime Roxetil?', 'Renal insufficiency: Dose adjustments may be necessary for patients with reduced urinary output.\r\nProlonged use: Can lead to overgrowth of non-susceptible organisms, so regular monitoring is required.\r\nUse with diuretics: Caution is advised in patients receiving potent diuretics.', 'what-precautions-should-be-taken-when-using-cefpodoxime-roxetil', NULL, '2025-01-07 13:06:07', '2025-01-07 13:06:07'),
(401, '76', 'Is Cefpodoxime Roxetil safe for pregnant or breastfeeding women?', 'Pregnancy: There are no adequate studies in pregnant women, but animal studies show no teratogenic effects. Use during pregnancy only if clearly necessary.\r\nBreastfeeding: Cefpodoxime is excreted in breast milk. A decision should be made whether to discontinue breastfeeding or the drug.', 'is-cefpodoxime-roxetil-safe-for-pregnant-or-breastfeeding-women', NULL, '2025-01-07 13:06:27', '2025-01-07 13:06:27'),
(402, '76', 'How should Cefpodoxime Roxetil suspension be reconstituted?', 'For a 50 ml suspension:\r\nAdd 30 ml (6 teaspoonfuls) of cooled, boiled water to the bottle.\r\nShake well after each addition until the powder is fully dissolved.\r\nShake the suspension before each use.\r\nStorage: Keep the bottle tightly closed and store it in a refrigerator.\r\nDiscard unused suspension after 14 days.', 'how-should-cefpodoxime-roxetil-suspension-be-reconstituted', NULL, '2025-01-07 13:08:02', '2025-01-07 13:08:02'),
(403, '76', 'What drug interactions should be monitored when using Cefpodoxime Roxetil?', 'Antacids (e.g., sodium bicarbonate, aluminum hydroxide): May reduce plasma levels by 24%-42%.\r\nH2 blockers: Decrease absorption by 27%-32%.', 'what-drug-interactions-should-be-monitored-when-using-cefpodoxime-roxetil', NULL, '2025-01-07 13:08:21', '2025-01-07 13:08:21'),
(404, '77', 'What are the available formulations of Rozith?', 'Rozith 250 Tablet: Contains Azithromycin Dihydrate USP, equivalent to Azithromycin 250 mg.\r\nRozith 500 Tablet: Contains Azithromycin Dihydrate USP, equivalent to Azithromycin 500 mg.\r\nRozith Powder for Suspension: When reconstituted, each 5 ml suspension contains Azithromycin Dihydrate USP, equivalent to Azithromycin 200 mg.', 'what-are-the-available-formulations-of-rozith', NULL, '2025-01-07 14:08:54', '2025-01-07 14:08:54'),
(405, '77', 'How does Azithromycin work?', 'Azithromycin binds to the 50S ribosomal subunit of susceptible organisms, interfering with microbial protein synthesis, which inhibits bacterial growth.', 'how-does-azithromycin-work', NULL, '2025-01-07 14:09:11', '2025-01-07 14:09:11'),
(406, '77', 'What are the contraindications for using Rozith?', 'Rozith is contraindicated in patients with known hypersensitivity to:\r\nAzithromycin\r\nErythromycin\r\nAny macrolide or ketolide antibiotics.', 'what-are-the-contraindications-for-using-rozith', NULL, '2025-01-07 14:09:49', '2025-01-07 14:09:49'),
(407, '77', 'What precautions should be taken when using Rozith?', 'Hepatic Function: Use with caution in patients with impaired liver function, as the liver is the main route of Azithromycin elimination.\r\nAllergic Reactions: Discontinue immediately if any allergic reaction occurs and provide appropriate therapy.', 'what-precautions-should-be-taken-when-using-rozith', NULL, '2025-01-07 14:10:30', '2025-01-07 14:10:30'),
(408, '77', 'What are the common side effects of Azithromycin?', 'Gastrointestinal: Diarrhea, nausea, abdominal pain, flatulence, and melena.\r\nAllergic Reactions: Rash, edema, urticaria, and rare serious hypersensitivity reactions.\r\nOthers: Transient, mild reductions in neutrophil counts (causal relationship not established).', 'what-are-the-common-side-effects-of-azithromycin', NULL, '2025-01-07 14:11:26', '2025-01-07 14:11:26'),
(409, '77', 'Is Rozith safe to use during pregnancy and lactation?', 'Pregnancy: Classified as Pregnancy Category B. Animal studies show no harm to the fetus, but use during pregnancy only if clearly needed.\r\nLactation: It is unknown if Azithromycin is excreted in human milk, so caution is advised when administering to nursing women.', 'is-rozith-safe-to-use-during-pregnancy-and-lactation', NULL, '2025-01-07 14:11:48', '2025-01-07 14:11:48'),
(410, '77', 'Is Rozith safe for children?', 'Yes, Azithromycin is safe and effective for children aged 6 months and older.', 'is-rozith-safe-for-children', NULL, '2025-01-07 14:12:15', '2025-01-07 14:12:15'),
(411, '77', 'What drug interactions should be considered with Rozith?', 'With Medicines:\r\nDigoxin: May increase digoxin concentration; monitor closely.\r\nErgot derivatives: May pose a theoretical risk of ergotism.\r\nNo significant pharmacokinetic interactions observed with warfarin, theophylline, carbamazepine, methylprednisolone, or cimetidine.\r\nWith Food and Antacids:\r\nFood and antacids reduce Azithromycin absorption. Administer 1 hour before or 2 hours after meals or antacids.', 'what-drug-interactions-should-be-considered-with-rozith', NULL, '2025-01-07 14:12:39', '2025-01-07 14:12:39'),
(412, '77', 'What should be done in case of an overdose of Rozith?', 'Overdosage may result in symptoms like tinnitus and ototoxicity, similar to those at normal doses but occurring more frequently.\r\nProvide general symptomatic and supportive care.', 'what-should-be-done-in-case-of-an-overdose-of-rozith', NULL, '2025-01-07 14:12:59', '2025-01-07 14:12:59'),
(413, '77', 'How should Rozith be stored?', 'Store at a temperature not exceeding 30C in a dry place.\r\nProtect from light and moisture.', 'how-should-rozith-be-stored', NULL, '2025-01-07 14:13:19', '2025-01-07 14:13:19'),
(414, '78', 'What is the presentation of Yonex?', 'Yonex for IV/IM Injection 150 mg: Each vial contains Colistimethate Sodium USP, equivalent to Colistin 150 mg or 4.5 million IU.', 'what-is-the-presentation-of-yonex', NULL, '2025-01-07 14:59:31', '2025-01-07 14:59:31'),
(415, '78', 'How does Colistimethate Sodium work?', 'Colistimethate Sodium is a surface-active agent that penetrates and disrupts bacterial cell membranes, exhibiting bactericidal activity against aerobic gram-negative microorganisms like Enterobacter aerogenes, Escherichia coli, Klebsiella pneumoniae, and Pseudomonas aeruginosa.', 'how-does-colistimethate-sodium-work', NULL, '2025-01-07 14:59:52', '2025-01-07 14:59:52'),
(416, '78', 'What are the indications for Yonex?', 'Yonex is indicated for the treatment of acute or chronic infections caused by sensitive strains of gram-negative bacilli, particularly Pseudomonas aeruginosa. It is effective against:\r\nEnterobacter aerogenes\r\nEscherichia coli\r\nKlebsiella pneumoniae\r\nPseudomonas aeruginosa\r\nNote: It is not effective against Proteus or Neisseria.', 'what-are-the-indications-for-yonex', NULL, '2025-01-07 15:00:18', '2025-01-07 15:00:18'),
(417, '78', 'How should Yonex be reconstituted?', 'Reconstitute the 150 mg vial with 2.0 mL of sterile Water for Injection, USP.\r\nThe reconstituted solution contains Colistimethate Sodium at a concentration equivalent to 75 mg/mL of colistin base activity.\r\nGently swirl during reconstitution to avoid frothing.\r\nInspect for particulate matter or discoloration before administration. Do not use if abnormalities are observed.', 'how-should-yonex-be-reconstituted', NULL, '2025-01-07 15:00:43', '2025-01-07 15:00:43'),
(418, '78', 'What is the dosage for Yonex?', 'Adults and Pediatric Patients: Administer in 2 to 4 divided doses, with a total daily dose of 2.55 mg/kg/day for patients with normal renal function.\r\nObese Patients: Base dosage on ideal body weight.\r\nRenal Impairment: Reduce dosage based on renal function.', 'what-is-the-dosage-for-yonex', NULL, '2025-01-07 15:01:02', '2025-01-07 15:01:02'),
(419, '78', 'How should Yonex be administered intravenously?', 'Direct Intermittent Administration: Slowly inject half of the total daily dose over 35 minutes every 12 hours.\r\nContinuous Infusion: Inject half of the daily dose over 35 minutes, then add the remaining half to an infusion solution (e.g., 0.9% NaCl, 5% dextrose). Administer the second half via slow IV infusion over 2223 hours.\r\nNote: Prepare infusion solutions freshly and use within 24 hours.', 'how-should-yonex-be-administered-intravenously', NULL, '2025-01-07 15:01:22', '2025-01-07 15:01:22'),
(420, '78', 'What are the contraindications for Yonex?', 'Yonex is contraindicated in patients with known hypersensitivity to Colistimethate Sodium or any of its components.', 'what-are-the-contraindications-for-yonex', NULL, '2025-01-07 15:01:39', '2025-01-07 15:01:39'),
(421, '78', 'What are the warnings and precautions for Yonex?', 'Maximum Daily Dose: Do not exceed 5 mg/kg/day in patients with normal renal function.\r\nNeurological Disturbances: May cause paresthesia, dizziness, vertigo, and slurred speech. Patients should avoid hazardous activities during therapy.\r\nNephrotoxicity: Monitor renal function closely; effects are reversible upon discontinuation.\r\nClostridium difficile-Associated Diarrhea (CDAD): Discontinue unnecessary antibiotics and manage appropriately.\r\nOverdosage Risks: Includes renal insufficiency, muscle weakness, apnea, or respiratory arrest.', 'what-are-the-warnings-and-precautions-for-yonex', NULL, '2025-01-07 15:02:04', '2025-01-07 15:02:04'),
(422, '78', 'What are the common side effects of Yonex?', 'Gastrointestinal: Upset stomach.\r\nNeurological: Tingling of extremities, slurred speech, dizziness, vertigo, paresthesia.\r\nDermatological: Itching, urticaria, rash.\r\nOther: Fever, increased BUN, elevated creatinine, decreased urine output, respiratory distress, apnea, nephrotoxicity.', 'what-are-the-common-side-effects-of-yonex', NULL, '2025-01-07 15:02:24', '2025-01-07 15:02:24'),
(423, '78', 'Is Yonex safe to use during pregnancy and lactation?', 'Pregnancy: Classified as Category C. Use with caution as safety in human pregnancies is not established.\r\nLactation: Colistin Sulfate is known to be excreted in human milk; caution is advised when administering to nursing women.', 'is-yonex-safe-to-use-during-pregnancy-and-lactation', NULL, '2025-01-07 15:02:43', '2025-01-07 15:02:43'),
(424, '78', 'Can Yonex be used in children?', 'Yes, it is safe for neonates, infants, children, and adolescents. Pediatric patients should be closely monitored as they may not report symptoms of toxicity.', 'can-yonex-be-used-in-children', NULL, '2025-01-07 15:03:01', '2025-01-07 15:03:01'),
(425, '78', 'What drug interactions should be considered with Yonex?', 'Avoid concomitant use with aminoglycosides or polymyxins unless necessary.\r\nCurariform muscle relaxants, ether, succinylcholine, gallamine, and sodium cephalothin may enhance nephrotoxicity.', 'what-drug-interactions-should-be-considered-with-yonex', NULL, '2025-01-07 15:03:21', '2025-01-07 15:03:21'),
(426, '78', 'What are the symptoms of Yonex overdosage?', 'Symptoms include paresthesia, lethargy, confusion, ataxia, respiratory arrest, and muscle paralysis, which may lead to death.\r\nDiscontinue therapy immediately and provide supportive care.', 'what-are-the-symptoms-of-yonex-overdosage', NULL, '2025-01-07 15:03:40', '2025-01-07 15:03:40'),
(427, '78', 'How should Yonex be stored?', 'Store below 25C in a dry place, protected from light and moisture.\r\nUse reconstituted solution immediately or store in a refrigerator (28C) for up to 24 hours.', 'how-should-yonex-be-stored', NULL, '2025-01-07 15:04:00', '2025-01-07 15:04:00'),
(428, '79', 'What is the composition of Zopime?', 'Zopime 500 mg IV/IM Injection: Each vial contains sterile Cefepime Hydrochloride with L-Arginine USP, equivalent to Cefepime 500 mg.\r\nZopime 1 g IV/IM Injection: Each vial contains sterile Cefepime Hydrochloride with L-Arginine USP, equivalent to Cefepime 1 g.', 'what-is-the-composition-of-zopime', NULL, '2025-01-07 15:18:21', '2025-01-07 15:18:21'),
(429, '79', 'How does Zopime work?', 'Zopime (Cefepime Hydrochloride) is a fourth-generation cephalosporin antibiotic that disrupts the synthesis of the peptidoglycan layer of bacterial cell walls, essential for maintaining structural integrity, leading to bacterial cell death.', 'how-does-zopime-work', NULL, '2025-01-07 15:18:32', '2025-01-07 15:18:32'),
(430, '79', 'What are the indications for Zopime?', 'Zopime is indicated for the treatment of infections caused by susceptible bacteria in adults, including:\r\nLower respiratory tract infections (pneumonia, bronchitis).\r\nUrinary tract infections (complicated and uncomplicated).\r\nSkin and skin structure infections.\r\nSepticemia.\r\nIntra-abdominal infections (peritonitis, biliary tract infections).\r\nEmpiric treatment of febrile neutropenia.', 'what-are-the-indications-for-zopime', NULL, '2025-01-07 15:18:54', '2025-01-07 15:18:54'),
(431, '79', 'How should Zopime be reconstituted?', 'Vial Size   	Diluent Volume (mL)\r\n500 mg IV	5.0\r\n500 mg IM	1.3\r\n1 g IV	10.0\r\n1 g IM	2.4', 'how-should-zopime-be-reconstituted', NULL, '2025-01-07 15:19:29', '2025-01-07 15:19:29'),
(432, '79', 'What are the contraindications for Zopime?', 'Zopime is contraindicated in patients with a history of immediate hypersensitivity reactions to:\r\nCefepime.\r\nCephalosporins.\r\nPenicillins.\r\nOther beta-lactam antibiotics.', 'what-are-the-contraindications-for-zopime', NULL, '2025-01-07 15:19:53', '2025-01-07 15:19:53'),
(433, '79', 'What precautions should be taken while using Zopime?', 'Overgrowth of non-susceptible organisms: Prolonged use may result in superinfections.\r\nAllergic reactions: Discontinue use if allergic reactions occur.\r\nRenal function: Dosage adjustment is required in patients with impaired renal function.', 'what-precautions-should-be-taken-while-using-zopime', NULL, '2025-01-07 15:20:14', '2025-01-07 15:20:14'),
(434, '79', 'What are the common side effects of Zopime?', 'System	Side Effects\r\nHypersensitivity	Rash (1.8%), pruritus, urticaria.\r\nGastrointestinal	Nausea, vomiting, oral moniliasis, diarrhea (1.2%), colitis.\r\nCNS	Headache.\r\nOther	Fever, vaginitis, erythema.', 'what-are-the-common-side-effects-of-zopime', NULL, '2025-01-07 15:20:39', '2025-01-07 15:20:39'),
(435, '79', 'Can Zopime be used during pregnancy and lactation?', 'Pregnancy: Classified as Category B. Use only if clearly needed.\r\nLactation: Cefepime is excreted in human breast milk in low concentrations. Caution is advised.', 'can-zopime-be-used-during-pregnancy-and-lactation', NULL, '2025-01-07 15:20:57', '2025-01-07 15:20:57'),
(436, '79', 'Can Zopime be used in pediatric and geriatric patients?', 'Pediatric Use: Safe for patients 2 months and older. Not established for patients under 2 months of age.\r\nGeriatric Use: Dosage adjustments required for renal insufficiency.', 'can-zopime-be-used-in-pediatric-and-geriatric-patients', NULL, '2025-01-07 15:21:16', '2025-01-07 15:21:16'),
(437, '79', 'Are there any drug interactions with Zopime?', 'Aminoglycosides: Increased risk of nephrotoxicity and ototoxicity when used concurrently.\r\nPotent diuretics (e.g., furosemide): May increase nephrotoxicity risk.', 'are-there-any-drug-interactions-with-zopime', NULL, '2025-01-07 15:21:34', '2025-01-07 15:21:34'),
(438, '79', 'What should be done in case of overdosage?', 'Overdosage may result in seizures, encephalopathy, and neuromuscular excitability.\r\nImmediate supportive care and monitoring are required. Dialysis may help remove Cefepime from circulation.', 'what-should-be-done-in-case-of-overdosage', NULL, '2025-01-07 15:21:53', '2025-01-07 15:21:53'),
(439, '79', 'How should Zopime be stored?', 'Store in a cool, dry place below 25C.', 'how-should-zopime-be-stored', NULL, '2025-01-07 15:22:11', '2025-01-07 15:22:11'),
(440, '80', 'What is Teicoplanin?', 'Teicoplanin is a glycopeptide antibiotic produced by Actinoplanes teichomyceticus. It is supplied as a sterile, pyrogen-free, ivory-white powder for reconstitution with water for injection. Upon reconstitution, it forms a clear solution.', 'what-is-teicoplanin', NULL, '2025-01-07 15:49:15', '2025-01-07 15:49:15'),
(441, '80', 'How does Teicoplanin work?', 'Teicoplanin inhibits the growth of susceptible organisms by interfering with cell wall biosynthesis. It specifically binds to D-alanyl-D-alanine residues, blocking peptidoglycan synthesis at a site different from beta-lactams.', 'how-does-teicoplanin-work', NULL, '2025-01-07 15:49:33', '2025-01-07 15:49:33'),
(442, '80', 'What are the indications for Teicoplanin?', 'Teicoplanin is indicated for the treatment of the following infections in adults and children:\r\nComplicated skin and soft tissue infections.\r\nBone and joint infections.\r\nHospital-acquired pneumonia.\r\nCommunity-acquired pneumonia.\r\nComplicated urinary tract infections.\r\nInfective endocarditis.\r\nClostridium difficile-associated diarrhea and colitis (alternative oral treatment).', 'what-are-the-indications-for-teicoplanin', NULL, '2025-01-07 15:49:54', '2025-01-07 15:49:54'),
(443, '80', 'How is Teicoplanin administered?', 'Teicoplanin can be administered intravenously (bolus injection or infusion) or intramuscularly. For neonates, only intravenous infusion is recommended.\r\n\r\nIV Bolus Injection: Over 35 minutes.\r\nIV Infusion: Over 30 minutes.', 'how-is-teicoplanin-administered', NULL, '2025-01-07 15:50:17', '2025-01-07 15:50:17'),
(444, '80', 'What is the dosage for adults with normal kidney function?', 'Standard Dose: 6 mg/kg (usually 400 mg) IV on the first day, followed by 6 mg/kg (400 mg) IV or 3 mg/kg (200 mg) IV/IM daily.\r\nSevere Infections: Start with 6 mg/kg (400 mg) twice daily for 14 days, followed by 6 mg/kg/day IV.', 'what-is-the-dosage-for-adults-with-normal-kidney-function', NULL, '2025-01-07 15:50:38', '2025-01-07 15:50:38'),
(445, '80', 'What adjustments are required for adults with kidney failure?', 'Moderate Kidney Failure (Creatinine Clearance 4060 ml/min): Halve the daily dose or administer on alternate days.\r\nSevere Kidney Failure (Creatinine Clearance <40 ml/min) or Hemodialysis Patients: Reduce the daily dose to one-third or administer every three days.', 'what-adjustments-are-required-for-adults-with-kidney-failure', NULL, '2025-01-07 15:50:57', '2025-01-07 15:50:57'),
(446, '80', 'What is the dosage for children?', 'Ages 2 months to 12 years: 10 mg/kg every 12 hours for three doses, then 610 mg/kg/day.\r\nNeonates (up to 2 months): 16 mg/kg on the first day, followed by 8 mg/kg/day by slow IV infusion.\r\nChildren with Kidney Failure: Adjust doses as per adult guidelines.', 'what-is-the-dosage-for-children', NULL, '2025-01-07 15:51:16', '2025-01-07 15:51:16'),
(447, '80', 'What is the dosage for Clostridium difficile-associated diarrhea?', '100200 mg twice daily for 714 days.', 'what-is-the-dosage-for-clostridium-difficile-associated-diarrhea', NULL, '2025-01-07 15:51:35', '2025-01-07 15:51:35'),
(448, '80', 'What is the role of Teicoplanin in combination therapy?', 'Teicoplanin can be combined with other bactericidal antibiotics for:\r\nMaximum bactericidal activity.\r\nTreating infections where Gram-negative bacteria cannot be ruled out (e.g., empirical treatment of febrile neutropenia).', 'what-is-the-role-of-teicoplanin-in-combination-therapy', NULL, '2025-01-07 15:51:52', '2025-01-07 15:51:52'),
(449, '80', 'How long does it take for Teicoplanin to show effects?', 'Most patients respond within 4872 hours. Total treatment duration depends on the infection type and severity:\r\n\r\nEndocarditis and osteomyelitis require at least three weeks of treatment.', 'how-long-does-it-take-for-teicoplanin-to-show-effects', NULL, '2025-01-07 15:52:13', '2025-01-07 15:52:13');
INSERT INTO `overviews` (`id`, `P_id`, `question`, `answare`, `slug`, `sequece`, `created_at`, `updated_at`) VALUES
(450, '80', 'How should Teicoplanin be reconstituted?', 'Inject 3 mL of water for injection into the 200 mg or 400 mg powder vial.\r\nGently rotate the vial between your hands to dissolve the powder, avoiding foaming.\r\nAllow foam, if present, to dissipate (approximately 15 minutes).\r\nUse only clear, yellowish solutions.', 'how-should-teicoplanin-be-reconstituted', NULL, '2025-01-07 15:52:36', '2025-01-07 15:52:36'),
(451, '80', 'What solutions can be used for infusion?', 'Sodium chloride 0.9%.\r\nRinger solution.\r\nRinger-lactate solution.\r\n5% dextrose solution.\r\n10% dextrose solution.\r\n0.18% sodium chloride and 4% glucose solution.\r\n0.45% sodium chloride and 5% glucose solution.', 'what-solutions-can-be-used-for-infusion', NULL, '2025-01-07 15:52:57', '2025-01-07 15:52:57'),
(452, '80', 'What are the contraindications for Teicoplanin?', 'Teicoplanin is contraindicated in patients with known hypersensitivity to the drug.', 'what-are-the-contraindications-for-teicoplanin', NULL, '2025-01-07 15:53:26', '2025-01-07 15:53:26'),
(453, '80', 'What precautions should be taken while using Teicoplanin?', 'Cross-hypersensitivity: Use cautiously in patients allergic to vancomycin.\r\nMonitoring: Regular monitoring of kidney function is recommended.', 'what-precautions-should-be-taken-while-using-teicoplanin', NULL, '2025-01-07 15:53:50', '2025-01-07 15:53:50'),
(454, '80', 'Can Teicoplanin be used during pregnancy and lactation?', 'Pregnancy: Category B3. Use only if the potential benefits outweigh risks.\r\nLactation: Use cautiously.', 'can-teicoplanin-be-used-during-pregnancy-and-lactation', NULL, '2025-01-07 15:54:10', '2025-01-07 15:54:10'),
(455, '80', 'What are the potential drug interactions with Teicoplanin?', 'Administer cautiously with nephrotoxic or ototoxic drugs, including:\r\nAminoglycosides.\r\nAmphotericin B.\r\nCyclosporine.\r\nFurosemide.', 'what-are-the-potential-drug-interactions-with-teicoplanin', NULL, '2025-01-07 15:54:36', '2025-01-07 15:54:36'),
(456, '80', 'How should Teicoplanin be stored?', 'Store below 30C in a dry place, protected from light.\r\nUse reconstituted solutions immediately or refrigerate (28C) for up to 24 hours.', 'how-should-teicoplanin-be-stored', NULL, '2025-01-07 15:54:55', '2025-01-07 15:54:55'),
(457, '81', 'What is Zoventa?', 'Zoventa is a brand name for Ceftibuten, a semisynthetic cephalosporin antibiotic used to treat various bacterial infections.', 'what-is-zoventa', NULL, '2025-01-07 16:44:33', '2025-01-07 16:44:33'),
(458, '81', 'What is the active ingredient in Zoventa?', 'The active ingredient in Zoventa is Ceftibuten Dihydrate.', 'what-is-the-active-ingredient-in-zoventa', NULL, '2025-01-07 16:44:53', '2025-01-07 16:44:53'),
(459, '81', 'How is Zoventa administered?', 'Zoventa is available in both capsule and suspension forms, typically taken orally.', 'how-is-zoventa-administered', NULL, '2025-01-07 16:45:12', '2025-01-07 16:45:12'),
(460, '81', 'What are the indications for Zoventa?', 'Zoventa (Ceftibuten) is used to treat infections caused by susceptible bacteria, including:\r\nRespiratory tract infections.\r\nUrinary tract infections.\r\nSkin and soft tissue infections.\r\nSome types of ear infections.', 'what-are-the-indications-for-zoventa', NULL, '2025-01-07 16:45:30', '2025-01-07 16:45:30'),
(461, '81', 'What is the usual dosage of Zoventa?', 'Dosage varies depending on the infection type and patient characteristics (e.g., age, kidney function). For adults with normal kidney function, typical dosages are:\r\n\r\n200 mg to 400 mg once daily, depending on the severity of the infection.\r\nFor children, the dose is adjusted based on weight.', 'what-is-the-usual-dosage-of-zoventa', NULL, '2025-01-07 16:45:48', '2025-01-07 16:45:48'),
(462, '81', 'What are the side effects of Zoventa?', 'Reported side effects of Zoventa include:\r\n\r\nGeneral: Aphasia, jaundice, melena, psychosis, stridor.\r\nSevere: Toxic epidermal necrolysis, serum sickness-like reactions, Stevens-Johnson syndrome.', 'what-are-the-side-effects-of-zoventa', NULL, '2025-01-07 16:46:10', '2025-01-07 16:46:10'),
(463, '81', 'What precautions should be taken when using Zoventa?', 'Prolonged use may lead to resistant organisms.\r\nDose adjustments are required for patients with kidney impairment.\r\nMonitor patients on prolonged therapy for any signs of superinfection.', 'what-precautions-should-be-taken-when-using-zoventa', NULL, '2025-01-07 16:46:30', '2025-01-07 16:46:30'),
(464, '81', 'Can Zoventa be used during pregnancy and lactation?', 'Pregnancy: Category B. It should be used during pregnancy only if clearly needed.\r\nLactation: It is unknown if Zoventa is excreted in human milk, so it should be used with caution in nursing mothers.', 'can-zoventa-be-used-during-pregnancy-and-lactation', NULL, '2025-01-07 16:46:49', '2025-01-07 16:46:49'),
(465, '81', 'Are there any contraindications for Zoventa?', 'Zoventa is contraindicated in patients who are allergic to Ceftibuten or other cephalosporin antibiotics.', 'are-there-any-contraindications-for-zoventa', NULL, '2025-01-07 16:47:11', '2025-01-07 16:47:11'),
(466, '81', 'How should Zoventa be stored?', 'Zoventa should be stored at a temperature not exceeding 30C in a dry place. Protect from light and moisture. Keep out of reach of children.', 'how-should-zoventa-be-stored', NULL, '2025-01-07 16:47:30', '2025-01-07 16:47:30'),
(467, '81', 'How is Zoventa\'s suspension form reconstituted?', 'Shake the bottle to loosen the powder.\r\nAdd 40 ml of boiled and cooled water, in increments of 5 ml at a time.\r\nShake well for 12 minutes to create a homogeneous suspension.', 'how-is-zoventas-suspension-form-reconstituted', NULL, '2025-01-07 16:47:59', '2025-01-07 16:47:59'),
(468, '81', 'What should be done in case of an overdose of Zoventa?', 'An overdose of Zoventa may cause symptoms like cerebral irritation leading to convulsions. Zoventa is dialyzable, with 65% of the plasma concentration removable by hemodialysis.', 'what-should-be-done-in-case-of-an-overdose-of-zoventa', NULL, '2025-01-07 16:48:16', '2025-01-07 16:48:16'),
(469, '82', 'What is Zydus?', 'Zydus is a brand name for Moxifloxacin, a fluoroquinolone antibiotic with a broad spectrum of antibacterial activity.', 'what-is-zydus', NULL, '2025-01-07 17:10:42', '2025-01-07 17:10:42'),
(470, '82', 'What class of antibiotic does Zydus belong to?', 'Zydus (Moxifloxacin) is a member of the fluoroquinolones class of antibiotics.', 'what-class-of-antibiotic-does-zydus-belong-to', NULL, '2025-01-07 17:11:07', '2025-01-07 17:11:07'),
(471, '82', 'How does Zydus work?', 'Zydus exerts its bactericidal action by inhibiting topoisomerase II (DNA gyrase) and topoisomerase IV, enzymes required for bacterial DNA replication, transcription, and repair.', 'how-does-zydus-work', NULL, '2025-01-07 17:11:36', '2025-01-07 17:11:36'),
(472, '82', 'What types of infections is Zydus used to treat?', 'Zydus is indicated for the treatment of infections caused by susceptible bacteria, including:\r\n\r\nAcute Bacterial Sinusitis\r\nAcute Bacterial Exacerbation of Chronic Bronchitis\r\nCommunity Acquired Pneumonia\r\nUncomplicated Skin and Skin Structure Infections\r\nComplicated Skin and Skin Structure Infections\r\nComplicated Intra-Abdominal Infections', 'what-types-of-infections-is-zydus-used-to-treat', NULL, '2025-01-07 17:11:55', '2025-01-07 17:11:55'),
(473, '82', 'What is the recommended dosage of Zydus?', 'The recommended dose of Zydus is 400 mg once daily. The duration of therapy depends on the type of infection being treated.', 'what-is-the-recommended-dosage-of-zydus', NULL, '2025-01-07 17:12:13', '2025-01-07 17:12:13'),
(474, '82', 'Are there any dosage adjustments needed for patients with renal or hepatic impairment?', 'No, dosage adjustments are not required for patients with renal or hepatic impairment.', 'are-there-any-dosage-adjustments-needed-for-patients-with-renal-or-hepatic-impairment', NULL, '2025-01-07 17:13:27', '2025-01-07 17:13:27'),
(475, '82', 'What are the contraindications for using Zydus?', 'Zydus is contraindicated in patients with known hypersensitivity to Moxifloxacin or other quinolone antibiotics.', 'what-are-the-contraindications-for-using-zydus', NULL, '2025-01-07 17:13:49', '2025-01-07 17:13:49'),
(476, '82', 'What are the common side effects of Zydus?', 'Most side effects are mild to moderate, including:\r\n\r\nNausea\r\nDiarrhea\r\nDizziness', 'what-are-the-common-side-effects-of-zydus', NULL, '2025-01-07 17:14:12', '2025-01-07 17:14:12'),
(477, '82', 'Can Zydus be used during pregnancy and lactation?', 'Pregnancy: Category C. Zydus should be used during pregnancy only if the potential benefits justify the potential risks to the fetus.\r\nNursing Mothers: Moxifloxacin may be excreted in human breast milk, and due to potential serious adverse reactions in infants, nursing mothers should decide whether to discontinue breastfeeding or discontinue the drug.', 'can-zydus-be-used-during-pregnancy-and-lactation', NULL, '2025-01-07 17:14:33', '2025-01-07 17:14:33'),
(478, '82', 'Is Zydus safe for pediatric patients?', 'Safety and effectiveness in pediatric patients and adolescents under 18 years of age have not been established.', 'is-zydus-safe-for-pediatric-patients', NULL, '2025-01-07 17:14:58', '2025-01-07 17:14:58'),
(479, '82', 'What precautions should be considered when using Zydus?', 'Zydus can prolong the QT interval, so it should be avoided in patients with QT prolongation, hypokalemia, or those on drugs that also prolong the QT interval.\r\nMoxifloxacin may increase the risk of tendinitis and tendon rupture. If tendon pain or inflammation occurs, the drug should be discontinued immediately.', 'what-precautions-should-be-considered-when-using-zydus', NULL, '2025-01-07 17:15:20', '2025-01-07 17:15:20'),
(480, '82', 'Are there any drug interactions with Zydus?', 'Antacids, sucralfate, multivitamins, and other products with multivalent cations may reduce the absorption of Moxifloxacin. It should be taken 4 hours before or 8 hours after these products.\r\nWarfarin: Moxifloxacin may enhance the anticoagulant effect of warfarin.\r\nClass IA and Class III antiarrhythmics: Concomitant use may increase the proarrhythmic effect, so it should be avoided.\r\nNo clinically significant interactions have been observed with theophylline, digoxin, or glyburide.', 'are-there-any-drug-interactions-with-zydus', NULL, '2025-01-07 17:15:43', '2025-01-07 17:15:43'),
(481, '82', 'What are the available pack sizes for Zydus?', 'Zydus is available in:\r\n\r\nZydus Tablet 400 mg: Each box contains 2  7 tablets in an Alu-Alu blister pack.', 'what-are-the-available-pack-sizes-for-zydus', NULL, '2025-01-07 17:16:02', '2025-01-07 17:16:02'),
(482, '82', 'How should Zydus be stored?', 'Zydus should be stored in a dry place, at a temperature not exceeding 30C, and protected from light and moisture.\r\n\r\nCaution: Keep out of reach of children.', 'how-should-zydus-be-stored', NULL, '2025-01-07 17:16:17', '2025-01-07 17:16:17'),
(483, '83', 'What is Edvila-M?', 'Edvila-M is a combination of two antihyperglycemic agents, Vildagliptin and Metformin Hydrochloride, used to improve glycemic control in patients with type 2 diabetes.', 'what-is-edvila-m', NULL, '2025-01-08 16:45:07', '2025-01-08 16:45:07'),
(484, '83', 'How does Edvila-M work?', 'Vildagliptin: A DPP-4 inhibitor that slows the inactivation of incretin hormones (GLP-1 and GIP). This increases insulin synthesis and release, while reducing glucagon secretion, leading to decreased hepatic glucose production.\r\nMetformin Hydrochloride: A biguanide that decreases hepatic glucose production, reduces intestinal glucose absorption, and enhances peripheral glucose uptake and utilization.', 'how-does-edvila-m-work', NULL, '2025-01-08 16:45:28', '2025-01-08 16:45:28'),
(485, '83', 'What is Edvila-M used for?', 'Edvila-M is indicated as an adjunct to diet and exercise to improve glycemic control in adults with type 2 diabetes mellitus when treatment with both Vildagliptin and Metformin is appropriate.', 'what-is-edvila-m-used-for', NULL, '2025-01-08 16:46:05', '2025-01-08 16:46:05'),
(486, '83', 'What is the recommended dosage of Edvila-M?', 'The starting dose is based on the patients current dose of Metformin: 50 mg/500 mg or 50 mg/850 mg twice daily (morning and evening).\r\nThe maximum daily dose is 100 mg Vildagliptin and 2000 mg Metformin HCl.\r\nDoses higher than 100 mg of Vildagliptin are not recommended.\r\nTo minimize gastrointestinal side effects, take Edvila-M with or just after food.', 'what-is-the-recommended-dosage-of-edvila-m', NULL, '2025-01-08 16:46:26', '2025-01-08 16:46:26'),
(487, '83', 'Who should not take Edvila-M?', 'Edvila-M is contraindicated in patients with:\r\nHypersensitivity to the active ingredients or excipients.\r\nRenal impairment (creatinine clearance <60 mL/min).\r\nAcute or chronic metabolic acidosis, including diabetic ketoacidosis.\r\nType 1 diabetes.', 'who-should-not-take-edvila-m', NULL, '2025-01-08 16:46:47', '2025-01-08 16:46:47'),
(488, '83', 'What precautions should be taken when using Edvila-M?', 'Lactic Acidosis: Rare but serious; discontinue treatment immediately if suspected.\r\nMonitor serum creatinine yearly in patients with normal renal function and more frequently in those with impaired renal function or elderly patients.\r\nConduct liver function tests (LFTs) before starting treatment, at 3-month intervals during the first year, and periodically thereafter.\r\nStop Edvila-M 48 hours before elective surgery requiring general anesthesia and resume it no earlier than 48 hours afterward.\r\nUse cautiously in elderly patients and monitor renal function regularly, especially with antihypertensives, diuretics, or NSAIDs.', 'what-precautions-should-be-taken-when-using-edvila-m', NULL, '2025-01-08 16:47:07', '2025-01-08 16:47:07'),
(489, '83', 'What are the common side effects of Edvila-M?', 'Common side effects include:\r\nTremor\r\nHeadache\r\nDizziness\r\nNausea\r\nHypoglycemia\r\nFatigue\r\nRare but serious side effects:\r\n\r\nLactic acidosis (due to Metformin).\r\nHepatic dysfunction.', 'what-are-the-common-side-effects-of-edvila-m', NULL, '2025-01-08 16:47:27', '2025-01-08 16:47:27'),
(490, '83', 'Can Edvila-M be used during pregnancy or breastfeeding?', 'Pregnancy: Avoid unless the potential benefit outweighs the risk, as no adequate data is available.\r\nBreastfeeding: Avoid use due to a lack of data on whether Vildagliptin is excreted in human milk.\r\n9. Is Edvila-M recommended for pediatric or geriatric patients?\r\n\r\nPediatric Use: Not recommended for patients under 18 years of age.\r\nGeriatric Use: Regularly monitor renal function. Not recommended for patients over 75 years due to insufficient studies.', 'can-edvila-m-be-used-during-pregnancy-or-breastfeeding', NULL, '2025-01-08 16:47:50', '2025-01-08 16:47:50'),
(491, '83', 'Does Edvila-M interact with other drugs?', 'No significant interactions with pioglitazone, metformin, glibenclamide, digoxin, warfarin, amlodipine, ramipril, valsartan, or simvastatin.\r\nPotential interactions:\r\nGlucose-lowering effects may be reduced by thiazides, corticosteroids, thyroid products, and sympathomimetics.\r\nAntihyperglycemic effects may be altered by glucocorticoids, beta-2 agonists, diuretics, and ACE inhibitors. Monitor blood glucose levels and adjust dosages as needed.', 'does-edvila-m-interact-with-other-drugs', NULL, '2025-01-08 16:48:13', '2025-01-08 16:48:13'),
(492, '83', 'How should Edvila-M be stored?', 'Store Edvila-M in a dry place at room temperature, protected from light and moisture.', 'how-should-edvila-m-be-stored', NULL, '2025-01-08 16:48:42', '2025-01-08 16:48:42'),
(493, '83', 'What should you do if lactic acidosis is suspected?', 'Immediately discontinue Edvila-M and hospitalize the patient for evaluation and treatment.', 'what-should-you-do-if-lactic-acidosis-is-suspected', NULL, '2025-01-08 16:48:58', '2025-01-08 16:48:58'),
(494, '84', 'What is EVAGLIP?', 'EVAGLIP is a combination oral medication containing Empagliflozin and Linagliptin, used to help control blood sugar levels in adults with type 2 diabetes.', 'what-is-evaglip', NULL, '2025-01-08 17:08:39', '2025-01-08 17:08:39'),
(495, '84', 'What are the available strengths of EVAGLIP?', 'EVAGLIP Tablet 10 mg/5 mg: Contains 10 mg Empagliflozin and 5 mg Linagliptin.\r\nEVAGLIP Tablet 25 mg/5 mg: Contains 25 mg Empagliflozin and 5 mg Linagliptin.', 'what-are-the-available-strengths-of-evaglip', NULL, '2025-01-08 17:08:57', '2025-01-08 17:08:57'),
(496, '84', 'What is EVAGLIP used for?', 'EVAGLIP is indicated as an adjunct to diet and exercise to improve glycemic control in adults with type 2 diabetes mellitus when treatment with both empagliflozin and linagliptin is appropriate.', 'what-is-evaglip-used-for', NULL, '2025-01-08 17:09:17', '2025-01-08 17:09:17'),
(497, '84', 'What is the recommended dosage of EVAGLIP?', 'Starting Dose: 10 mg Empagliflozin / 5 mg Linagliptin once daily in the morning, with or without food.\r\nMaximum Dose: 25 mg Empagliflozin / 5 mg Linagliptin once daily for patients tolerating the starting dose.', 'what-is-the-recommended-dosage-of-evaglip', NULL, '2025-01-08 17:09:36', '2025-01-08 17:09:36'),
(498, '84', 'Who should not take EVAGLIP?', 'EVAGLIP is contraindicated in patients with:\r\nHypersensitivity to empagliflozin, linagliptin, or any ingredients in the medication.\r\nSevere renal impairment, end-stage renal disease, or those on dialysis.', 'who-should-not-take-evaglip', NULL, '2025-01-08 17:09:53', '2025-01-08 17:09:53'),
(499, '84', 'What precautions should be taken while using EVAGLIP?', 'Pancreatitis: Discontinue if suspected or confirmed.\r\nHypotension: Monitor volume status, especially in patients with renal impairment or those on diuretics.\r\nRenal Impairment: Regularly monitor renal function, particularly in patients with an eGFR <60 mL/min/1.73 m.\r\nHypoglycemia: Adjust insulin or insulin secretagogues to reduce risk.\r\nGenital Mycotic and Urinary Tract Infections: Monitor and treat as needed.\r\nHypersensitivity: Discontinue if any reactions occur.\r\nIncreased LDL-C: Monitor and manage elevated LDL cholesterol.\r\nMacrovascular Outcomes: No evidence suggests EVAGLIP reduces macrovascular risk.', 'what-precautions-should-be-taken-while-using-evaglip', NULL, '2025-01-08 17:10:14', '2025-01-08 17:10:14'),
(500, '84', 'What are the common side effects of EVAGLIP?', 'Common Side Effects:\r\nUrinary tract infections, upper respiratory tract infections, genital yeast infections, increased urination, joint pain, nausea, and diarrhea.\r\nCold-like symptoms such as a runny or stuffy nose.', 'what-are-the-common-side-effects-of-evaglip', NULL, '2025-01-08 17:10:38', '2025-01-08 17:10:38'),
(501, '84', 'Can EVAGLIP be used during pregnancy or breastfeeding?', 'Pregnancy: Use only if the potential benefit outweighs the risk, as no adequate studies are available.\r\nLactation: Discontinue use as it is unknown if the drug is excreted in human milk.', 'can-evaglip-be-used-during-pregnancy-or-breastfeeding', NULL, '2025-01-08 17:10:56', '2025-01-08 17:10:56'),
(502, '84', 'Is EVAGLIP safe for children or elderly patients?', 'Pediatric Use: Not recommended, as safety and effectiveness have not been established.\r\nGeriatric Use: Monitor elderly patients closely due to a higher risk of adverse effects related to volume depletion and reduced renal function.', 'is-evaglip-safe-for-children-or-elderly-patients', NULL, '2025-01-08 17:11:21', '2025-01-08 17:11:21'),
(503, '84', 'How does renal impairment affect EVAGLIP usage?', 'Adverse effects related to reduced renal function are more common. Frequent renal function monitoring is necessary for patients with impaired kidneys.', 'how-does-renal-impairment-affect-evaglip-usage', NULL, '2025-01-08 17:11:52', '2025-01-08 17:11:52'),
(504, '84', 'What are the drug interactions with EVAGLIP?', 'Empagliflozin:\r\nMay increase urine volume when taken with diuretics, leading to potential volume depletion.\r\nRisk of hypoglycemia increases with insulin or insulin secretagogues.\r\nUrine glucose monitoring is not recommended as it increases urinary glucose excretion.\r\nLinagliptin:', 'what-are-the-drug-interactions-with-evaglip', NULL, '2025-01-08 17:12:50', '2025-01-08 17:12:50'),
(505, '84', 'What should be done in case of an overdose?', 'Seek immediate medical attention if an overdose is suspected.', 'what-should-be-done-in-case-of-an-overdose', NULL, '2025-01-08 17:13:16', '2025-01-08 17:13:16'),
(506, '84', 'How is EVAGLIP supplied?', 'EVAGLIP Tablet 10 mg/5 mg: Each box contains 3  10 tablets in Alu-Alu blister packs.\r\nEVAGLIP Tablet 25 mg/5 mg: Each box contains 3  10 tablets in Alu-Alu blister packs.', 'how-is-evaglip-supplied', NULL, '2025-01-08 17:13:35', '2025-01-08 17:13:35'),
(507, '84', 'How should EVAGLIP be stored?', 'Store EVAGLIP in a dry place at temperatures below 30C. Protect from light and moisture.', 'how-should-evaglip-be-stored', NULL, '2025-01-08 17:13:52', '2025-01-08 17:13:52'),
(508, '84', 'Is there any caution for storage?', 'Yes, always keep the medication out of reach of children.', 'is-there-any-caution-for-storage', NULL, '2025-01-08 17:14:13', '2025-01-08 17:14:13');
